1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:13,000
And I'll give a round of applause.

3
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Alright, so today is, I believe, the 11th of May 2013. We're in Seattle, Washington.

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:25,000
You're listening to the voice of David Klein for Virginia Tech.

5
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:29,000
Also on behalf of the Southern Oil History Program at UNC Chapel Hill.

6
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:34,000
Today, we are visiting with Aaron Dixon.

7
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:40,000
And behind the camera today is John Bishop from Media Generation and UCLA.

8
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:49,000
And this project is, this is the Civil Rights History Project for the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

9
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:54,000
So I just wanted to say thank you very much for making time for us being part of this project.

10
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:57,000
Okay, thank you.

11
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:11,000
And what I'd like to do to start is just start with your childhood, but tell us about the family into which you were born, where and how they may have been put together.

12
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Okay.

13
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:17,000
Let me see.

14
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:24,000
My mother, her parents came from Mississippi.

15
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:41,000
And she was heavily influenced by her great-grandmother, who was born in 1867.

16
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:48,000
And her mother was a slave.

17
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:57,000
At some point she got, you know, she became free and she lived a little life of a free woman.

18
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:04,000
But she was intertwined with the whole history of slavery.

19
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:16,000
And so her kids, particularly my great-great-grandmother Emma, you know, was born into the whole era of Jim Crow.

20
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:25,000
And, you know, it was very difficult for her to find work. The only work that Emma could find was at the Laundras.

21
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:29,000
And she worked for many, many years at the Laundras.

22
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:34,000
And she had, I believe, seven kids.

23
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:40,000
I think four of them died, you know, fairly young.

24
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:48,000
And her husband also died in a tragic accident because I believe he was a breakman.

25
00:02:48,000 --> 00:03:17,000
And so my grandmother, Emma's great-granddaughter, or no, Emma's granddaughter, actually, was a product of a relationship between a Jewish man and her mother.

26
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:22,000
And from what I understand, her mother was ostracized. This was a Mississippi.

27
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:29,000
Her mother was ostracized by the rest of the family because she had this relationship.

28
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:38,000
And so my grandmother's mother passed away when my grandmother was only three years old.

29
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:47,000
So she really didn't get to know her mother. And she didn't know anything about her father, the Jewish man.

30
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:59,000
And so eventually she was sent to Chicago to be raised by an aunt, her sisters, one of her mother's sisters.

31
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:09,000
And then part of the time she was raised by Emma, a good portion of the time she was raised by Emma in Mississippi.

32
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:17,000
So my grandmother met Roy Sledge, her husband.

33
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:35,000
And Roy's father was a blacksmith, one of the only few blacksmiths in Mississippi at the time who rode around in a white horse and would understand.

34
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:39,000
But for himself, he was some independence.

35
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:50,000
So my grandfather's belief, his mother was half-native American.

36
00:04:51,000 --> 00:05:00,000
So let me see.

37
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:08,000
So my mother was born to this union of Roy Sledge, who was half-native American.

38
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:26,000
And her mother, Josephine Sledge, who her birth name was Joe Willie, that was her birth name.

39
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:35,000
And so they moved to Chicago and it's part of the migration of Blackstone South.

40
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:44,000
And my mother was raised in Chicago and Milwaukee in St. Paul.

41
00:05:45,000 --> 00:06:02,000
So anyway, my grandfather Roy, he worked as a Pullman Porter, became an alcoholic and at times was a strange from the family.

42
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:10,000
Eventually he became sober in the States over further remaining years of his life.

43
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:17,000
And he was able to get a job at the post office where he retired.

44
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:29,000
Now, my mother, her mother, Josephine, had started her out at playing piano when she was five.

45
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:38,000
And she became a child prodigy on the piano and began playing costumes which she was seven years old.

46
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:48,000
And eventually, he would graduate from high school when she was 16.

47
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:53,000
Then we'll switch to my father's family.

48
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:59,000
My father's family came from Kentucky.

49
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:22,000
And his grand actually going back on his mother's side, their family inherited the plantation because of slave owners.

50
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:28,000
The slave owners had some relationship with my great-great-great-grandmother.

51
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:31,000
I think they had a relationship.

52
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:44,000
And so when he left, when slavery ended, he took his family to Denver and he gave the plantation to the woman that he had the relationship with.

53
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:59,000
And so, and also on my grandfather's side, his grandmother had two great-great-uncles who served in the Civil War.

54
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:06,000
And when they returned from the Civil War, they actually got land for being in the Civil War.

55
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:14,000
And they took that land. I'm not unclear where this land was but it was part of the land they got from the plantation.

56
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:17,000
And they started their own town called Brooksville.

57
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:19,000
So what side did they fight on?

58
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:21,000
They fought on the north.

59
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:28,000
There was some of the first black soldiers to volunteer to fight on the north.

60
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:45,000
And it goes further back, someone else on that side of the family has traced it back to royalty in Scotland where there's a coat of arms and all that kind of stuff.

61
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:57,000
So I just remember that my grandmother and my father's son always spoke very proudly of her family and her side of the family.

62
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:06,000
And in fact, in the house that she lived in in Chicago, they had a lot of furniture that came from that plantation.

63
00:09:06,000 --> 00:09:23,000
And now her father, I'm sorry, her husband, my father's father, was, I think maybe one quarter or maybe half Native American, but he never knew who his mother was.

64
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:30,000
He was raised by his aunt and his father left and went to St. Louis and became a millionaire.

65
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:44,000
And so my grandfather, his name was Elmer and my grandmother, Miljert, they met and they married and they moved.

66
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:53,000
And they had my father was born in Henderson, Kentucky and they moved to Chicago along with that great migration.

67
00:09:53,000 --> 00:10:05,000
And so my grandfather, my father's side, Elmer Dixon, he found work working for a wealthy Jewish man. I'm not sure what capacity.

68
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:14,000
But he was making enough money where he never allowed his wife to work. His wife never worked.

69
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:26,000
And so he had my father and he had another daughter, Doris, my aunt. And they were raised in Chicago.

70
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:41,000
And my father started taking classes at the Art Institute at a young age and he got a scholarship to the Art Institute at a young age.

71
00:10:41,000 --> 00:11:01,000
He was also captain of the ROTC in Chicago. And when World War II broke out, he saw the news at the movie theaters because that's where they had the news at, to movie theaters about the attack on Pearl Harbor.

72
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:08,000
And he runs down to the induction center and wants to join and he's told that we don't take boys like you.

73
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:18,000
So when he graduates though, the Army is right there waiting for him. And so he's drafted into the Army along with many of his fellow Black soldiers.

74
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:31,000
They sent to Mississippi and you know I talk about in my book, there's a lot of stories he talks about in Mississippi and the trials and tribulations of being in such a volatile place.

75
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:44,000
And as a member of the military and being Black and things get so bad that you know he writes his mother and is telling her what's going on and she writes Elmer Rhodes about.

76
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:47,000
And you know.

77
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:52,000
Can you talk this a little bit more about that so what kinds of things we're going on that people are going on?

78
00:11:52,000 --> 00:12:01,000
Yeah sure. Well one of the stories is that their him and his fellow soldiers are out on marching on, I think it's called Dipwreck.

79
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:13,000
And they're out marching in the hot sun and the hot humid Mississippi sun and they come across this farm.

80
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:18,000
They want to march across the farm so they won't have to go through the swamp.

81
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:34,000
And the White Officer asked the farmer if they could march across the farm, his field and the White farmer pointed shotgun at the soldiers and says no niggers are going to march across my field.

82
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:48,000
So they have to go through the swamps. But when they camp down that night my father and some of his friends go back and burn down the barn of the farmer.

83
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:55,000
Another story is that he meets a very light, conflicted woman in the small town near the base.

84
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:04,000
And you know in the deep south you know where they don't know who you are it becomes very dangerous.

85
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:16,000
And so he wants on their date they're out and he wants to walk her back across town home and she says no you know you probably shouldn't do that.

86
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:24,000
But you know being from Chicago you know the whole gentleman thing that's what you're supposed to do.

87
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:34,000
So he convinces her that that's what he's going to do and he's got a uniform on. So he walks her across town he's getting a lot of stairs at people.

88
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:47,000
And this white sergeant stops him and tells him you know boy when I come back through here you better not be here.

89
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:58,000
And so no you ask him why he's here what are you doing he says you know I'm walking my friend home he said well you better not be here when I get back.

90
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:09,000
So my father stops off at the post office on his way to walk her home and he writes his mother and tells the mother that his life is in danger.

91
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:19,000
So he continues walking her home and just you know fortunate that he didn't run into this sergeant and he makes it back to the base.

92
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:27,000
And this is another person in the army this is an even a local guy that's harassing him.

93
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:34,000
Oh this is the police. This is the town sheriff.

94
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:49,000
So the final incident was that I'm sure there are many others but him and his fellow soldiers were preparing to go on on furlough for the weekend.

95
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:57,000
And the sergeant comes in and tells him that their furlough is canceled that they have to clean.

96
00:14:57,000 --> 00:15:07,000
And so they refuse to do that and they start to riot and start drawing everything out onto the courtyard.

97
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:15,000
And this riot lasts for quite a while and finally they bring a train in and they ship them out.

98
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:18,000
And then my father finally goes to the Pacific theater.

99
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:23,000
Fights in the Philippines, fights in Okinawa.

100
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:31,000
While in Okinawa he sees a Marine cut the breast off over dead Japanese woman and hold it up in the air.

101
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:40,000
And my father just got lost control and grabbed his gun and was going to shoot this Marine.

102
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:47,000
But he stopped by you know his fellow comrades stopping from doing it.

103
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:50,000
And so after that incident he goes AWOL.

104
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:57,000
And he meets a Japanese family and I believe it was in Korea.

105
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:03,000
And he spends time with them and then he comes back.

106
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:08,000
And then he is sent back home.

107
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:17,000
And you know that changed his perspective of his nation, that incident, seeing what the Marine did.

108
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:31,000
And he started you know seeking out other things and he started being involved in Paul Robuson's youth brigade and starts you know flirting with the Communist Party.

109
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:38,000
I don't think he actually joined the Communist Party but you know he's flirting with the Communist Party.

110
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:42,000
So he gets out of the Army and he meets my mother.

111
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:51,000
They get married and he's a student at a junior college eventually goes to the Orange Institute and graduates.

112
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:57,000
And my mother has started teachers college and they started having kids.

113
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:04,000
And so my father gets a job at Shannu Air Force Base as a technical illustrator.

114
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:14,000
So the family moves to Champaign Illinois and we lived there for maybe about four years or so.

115
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:20,000
And there is a time I do remember when some men and black suits came to visit my father.

116
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:28,000
He didn't let him in the house. I'm assuming they were the FBI.

117
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:31,000
And then he gets a job offer.

118
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:35,000
I get several job offers and one of them is from Boeing and Seattle.

119
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:44,000
He remembers Seattle when he came through on this way back from the war and on this way to the war.

120
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:46,000
He spent time in Seattle.

121
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:49,000
So he thought it would be a good place to move his family.

122
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:56,000
So we moved to Seattle. I believe in 57, 58.

123
00:17:56,000 --> 00:18:01,000
And we move around.

124
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:05,000
So the black community in Seattle gets larger during the war, right?

125
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:08,000
Yeah, it does.

126
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:13,000
People coming in to work at Todd Shipyards, blacks coming in.

127
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:17,000
California, they're coming in to work in the munitions factories.

128
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:22,000
They're coming up here to work in airplane war factories.

129
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:31,000
And that's when a lot of black people do start coming west, is during the war.

130
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:32,000
We're back.

131
00:18:32,000 --> 00:18:35,000
We'll take your parts of town. We're black folks.

132
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:37,000
Yeah, it would mainly the central area.

133
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:41,000
The central area was primarily where black people lived.

134
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:51,000
So with Chinese and Filipinos and Japanese and some Native Americans.

135
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:56,000
Pretty much were all grouped up in this central area.

136
00:18:56,000 --> 00:18:59,000
And we see my parents.

137
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:04,000
We finally found a house that we were going to settle down in.

138
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:10,000
My parents brought a house in Majona neighborhood.

139
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:14,000
How did you describe that neighborhood?

140
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:21,000
Majona was a neighborhood of big old houses, lots of trees.

141
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:24,000
It's just really a really beautiful neighborhood.

142
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:27,000
It's connected to a series of other neighborhoods.

143
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:31,000
There's Harrison Valley. There's Majona.

144
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:35,000
There's Les Chi. There's Mount Baker.

145
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:38,000
And these are really nice neighborhoods.

146
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:41,000
And the lake is to the west, to the east.

147
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:45,000
So we've got views of the mountain, of the lake.

148
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:49,000
Not far from downtown.

149
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:56,000
It's really, it was very, really nice growing up in that neighborhood.

150
00:19:56,000 --> 00:20:04,000
And all those other neighborhoods, predominantly black, Filipino, Japanese, and Chinese.

151
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:07,000
All the grocery stores were all Chinese owned.

152
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:09,000
The little small grocery stores.

153
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:11,000
And they gave credit to everybody.

154
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:14,000
And we all went to school together.

155
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:17,000
All the Japanese, Filipino, and Chinese.

156
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:27,000
So growing up, it was almost like we didn't, it wasn't any distinction between our nationalities almost.

157
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:37,000
And then there were whites that still, that hadn't fled to Bellevue to the east side and other places that had stayed there.

158
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:46,000
And so it was, it was a, and those whites who had stayed were whites that had decided that they weren't going to move.

159
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:52,000
They were going to just kind of participate in this new thing that was happening.

160
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:55,000
You know, you're bringing your classes, those kids would be in your class.

161
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:58,000
Yes, yeah, yeah.

162
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:05,000
So it was really, we were really, very fortunate to grow up in that type of environment.

163
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:11,000
Now outside of those neighborhoods, you know, there was the usual racism.

164
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:13,000
You know, there was a police brutality.

165
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:16,000
There was a difficulty with finding jobs.

166
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:20,000
You know, my mother had a difficult time finding a job.

167
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:23,000
She had doors closed, closed on her.

168
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:24,000
Because of race.

169
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:25,000
Because of race.

170
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:27,000
Did you remember any particular?

171
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:30,000
Frederick and Nelson's, the store called Frederick and Nelson.

172
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:38,000
It's owned by Macy's now, but it was the main retail store, the largest retail store in Seattle, Frederick and Nelson's.

173
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:40,000
And she had a difficult time.

174
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:44,000
She was, you know, winning there one time when they had a sign open hiring.

175
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:47,000
And you know, she was told we're not hiring, you know.

176
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:50,000
So, but eventually she did get a job, you know.

177
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:58,000
And, you know, we, growing up, we lived right across the street from a park.

178
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:03,000
And the park was, had people there, you know, during the summertime.

179
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:05,000
And there was a lot of different programs.

180
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:09,000
And because, you know, there's the baby boom generation.

181
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:11,000
Just a lot of kids.

182
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:14,000
And people had big families.

183
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:19,000
You know, I'm talking about, our family was considerably small with four kids, you know.

184
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:22,000
Two brothers and a sister and myself.

185
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:27,000
But, you know, there were families that had like seven, eight kids, you know.

186
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:30,000
Big kids, I mean, big families.

187
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:35,000
And, you know, almost all of them were two parent families, you know.

188
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:39,000
And hard working, hard working parents.

189
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:45,000
And many of them had come from the south and other parts.

190
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:52,000
And so, and my father being an artist and my father, you know,

191
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:54,000
he loved other people of other cultures.

192
00:22:54,000 --> 00:23:01,000
You know, he just felt the need to always connect with people of other cultures.

193
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:08,000
And so, in doing so, he met some artists and people who were in the theater and other art.

194
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:13,000
And he got involved in the folk dancing group.

195
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:15,000
And they had a folk dancing group.

196
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:22,000
And it was, you know, people of, you know, Greek, Jewish, Italian, and Black.

197
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:29,000
And, you know, they met at different people's homes to do their dancing.

198
00:23:29,000 --> 00:23:32,000
And they met at our house quite often.

199
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:36,000
You know, I pulled the rug back and bring the wine out.

200
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:43,000
And the music and they were doing their folk dancing.

201
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:46,000
So, you know, this is kind of an environment we grew up in.

202
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:51,000
And all of us kids, we were required to play an instrument.

203
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:54,000
You know, all the kids were required to play an instrument.

204
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:57,000
This was my grandmother in Chicago.

205
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:05,000
My mother's mother, she was a very kind of dominating, kind of controlling type of woman, you know.

206
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:09,000
And so, she bought the instruments for everybody.

207
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:12,000
Everybody was going to play something.

208
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:16,000
And I was told I was going to play the violin.

209
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:26,000
So, not that I didn't like the violin I did, but I just never quite could grasp the whole reading notes and everything.

210
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:29,000
And I bought my violin home and it was broken one day.

211
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:31,000
And so, that was it for me.

212
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:33,000
My younger brother, he took up the violin.

213
00:24:33,000 --> 00:24:36,000
He played it all the way through to a guy away from high school.

214
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:38,000
Elmer played the trumpet.

215
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:41,000
He started out with the guitar.

216
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:44,000
And he played the trumpet all the way.

217
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:47,000
And my sister played the piano.

218
00:24:47,000 --> 00:24:50,000
So, my mother often played the piano.

219
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:55,000
And my father was, you know, trying to do his artwork on the side sometimes.

220
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:00,000
And he did have the showing of his artwork.

221
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:03,000
The Fry museum.

222
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:05,000
So, he was an illustrator, right?

223
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:07,000
Yeah, he was a technical illustrator.

224
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:16,000
And his friend, that boy who worked with him, they said he was the best artist out there.

225
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:23,000
So, but I know that he was really frustrated that he really didn't have the time,

226
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:28,000
the large amount of time that is needed to just really work on your art.

227
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:31,000
But he also was a poet as well.

228
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:34,000
And he wrote poetry.

229
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:38,000
And he exposed us to poetry.

230
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:42,000
You know, I learned Shakespeare from my father.

231
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:50,000
You know, I could quote different parts of Shakespeare because my father was doing it.

232
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:58,000
So, you know, we also participated in sports.

233
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:02,000
You know, my father didn't really push sports.

234
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:07,000
So, we kind of, you know, because we lived across the street from the park,

235
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:13,000
you know, we were very much involved in football, baseball, basketball, tennis.

236
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:15,000
We played a lot of tennis.

237
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:17,000
My brother, Michael, he played.

238
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:23,000
He got a scholarship to UCLA to play tennis and ping pong and all those things.

239
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:29,000
And we played in the tournaments with the Parks Department.

240
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:37,000
And then would there be incidents there playing on sports teams in terms of race at all?

241
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:42,000
Yeah, yeah, I mean, but there was, I mean, there was always fights amongst each other.

242
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:43,000
There was so many kids.

243
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:47,000
You know, there was always the fights, you know, we got in the fights.

244
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:55,000
But when we were on the softball team and we went to other areas like Ballard, Queen Anne,

245
00:26:55,000 --> 00:27:00,000
to say play other softball teams, yeah, there was a lot of tension and a lot of, you know,

246
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:03,000
calls going the wrong way.

247
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:08,000
And there was, yeah, there was a lot of, and people, black people didn't even go to Ballard.

248
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:10,000
You couldn't really go to Ballard.

249
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:16,000
Go to Queen Anne, you know, that was, that was unforbidden territory, particularly if you were young.

250
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:24,000
And even in high school, you know, you know, they turned into, in the fights and almost riots between, you know,

251
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:27,000
some of those schools Ballard and Queen Anne.

252
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:33,000
So, yeah, it was, it was, it was really extremely racially charged.

253
00:27:33,000 --> 00:27:38,000
A lot of times, you know, playing some of those teams.

254
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:48,000
And so, you know, even though we were in this cocoon, you know, there was always that element outside that racism that we always knew about,

255
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:51,000
and we always heard about, you know.

256
00:27:51,000 --> 00:28:02,000
Did you remember your folks talking to you about what it meant to be black or sort of how your own race consciousness to go?

257
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:04,000
Well, you know, we...

258
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:06,000
The artists were defined that long.

259
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:11,000
Yeah, well, you know, they never really, they just told stories.

260
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:15,000
They told stories, you know, that oral tradition.

261
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:21,000
You know, we got the stories from my grandparents, and we got stories from my great grandparents in our aunts,

262
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:28,000
and our uncles, whenever we were back Chicago, we were constantly hearing stories, and they were constantly telling us all the time.

263
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:36,000
And when they were talking amongst themselves, we would hear stories, you know, always, you know, this racism and things that are going on.

264
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:43,000
But I never, our parents never just directly said, this is that, and this is what's going on.

265
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:46,000
You know, but, you know, we were able to understand.

266
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:50,000
I remember when I was 13, and I said, I wanted to be a policeman.

267
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:54,000
My parents got real angry and said, no, you're not going to be no policeman.

268
00:28:54,000 --> 00:29:01,000
And I remember when I was 16 years old, and I said, I wanted to join the Marine and go into Vietnam.

269
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:03,000
And my father got angry.

270
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:10,000
I was angry as I've ever seen him, saying that, you know, no son of his is going to go to Vietnam.

271
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:15,000
And there were, you know, people going, being drafted to go to Vietnam all the time.

272
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:20,000
You know, a lot of people that we knew were in Vietnam.

273
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:23,000
So, his own experience.

274
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:26,000
His own experience. His own experience.

275
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:30,000
And so.

276
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:37,000
And have they involved you in politics at all, or I think wasn't there a visit when King came to town when you were in the city?

277
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:38,000
Yeah, yeah.

278
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:42,000
You know, we had, you know, political discussions.

279
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:44,000
We just had discussions in the kitchen.

280
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:46,000
The kitchen was always the place where we had this guy.

281
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:53,000
And the older we got, the more broader they got, and the more volatile they got.

282
00:29:53,000 --> 00:30:05,000
And so, let me see, when I was, you know, around 12 or 13 years old, I marched with Martin with the King when he came to Seattle.

283
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:10,000
Then I started getting involved in the demonstrations around town.

284
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:15,000
You know, I remember when George Wallace came to town, you know, we demonstrated against that.

285
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:17,000
And some other things.

286
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:20,000
And I was only like 12 or 13 or 14 years old.

287
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:23,000
So, I was only one of my brothers and sisters.

288
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:30,000
They weren't. I'm not sure how that happened, how I got involved, but I did.

289
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:35,000
I think it might have been through our church or something like that.

290
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:44,000
So, I graduated from high school in 1967 by the skin of my teeth.

291
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:52,000
And I had started working when I was a junior in high school.

292
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:58,000
I worked four times job. I worked and during the summer, I worked 14 hours a day.

293
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:04,000
Seven days a week. I bought my own clothes. I bought my own records.

294
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:08,000
I bought, I was determined I was going to be independent.

295
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:12,000
And so, I was added, I had a job and I didn't mind working, you know.

296
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:17,000
And even before that, you know, we are, most of us, my generation, we cut grass.

297
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:20,000
You know, we went to people's houses, we cut grass.

298
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:29,000
You know, I had a paper route when I was in middle school, I had in this seventh grade.

299
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:36,000
I had a paper route. We had to get up at six o'clock every morning and to go deliver papers.

300
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:40,000
And that was, it became too tough and too much of a strain.

301
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:45,000
I only had that for a month. But I almost got an evening paper route job.

302
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:49,000
He did after he came home from school. And so, I had to help him with that.

303
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:52,000
And he had that for a year.

304
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:55,000
Oh, right now.

305
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:57,000
Right now.

306
00:31:57,000 --> 00:31:59,000
No, you know.

307
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:02,000
You know, hear about that.

308
00:32:02,000 --> 00:32:05,000
Yeah, yeah, that's right.

309
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:13,000
So, yeah, I graduated and then I was trying to, you know, figure out what I was going to do.

310
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:18,000
You know, my parents had always told us we were going to go to college.

311
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:22,000
But I hadn't had any prospects yet.

312
00:32:22,000 --> 00:32:24,000
I wanted to go to Tennessee State.

313
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:27,000
And, you know, that's where my aunt went.

314
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:32,000
And most people, my age and older, were going to black colleges.

315
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:35,000
That's where their destination was.

316
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:37,000
And that's where I wanted to go to school.

317
00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:40,000
But my grades weren't good enough to get in Tennessee State.

318
00:32:40,000 --> 00:32:42,000
So, I was turned down.

319
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:44,000
So, I started.

320
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:49,000
And when Stokeley Carmichael came to town, I really got fired up.

321
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:54,000
You know, I, and I think Elmer was with me and my great friend, Michael Dean.

322
00:32:54,000 --> 00:33:00,000
And then I started wearing those Stokeley Carmichael glasses.

323
00:33:00,000 --> 00:33:11,000
I started, you know, really, really evolving and really growing in my understanding of what the racial politics was in America.

324
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:14,000
Would that have been when you first heard the term black power?

325
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:15,000
Yeah.

326
00:33:15,000 --> 00:33:16,000
Yeah.

327
00:33:16,000 --> 00:33:18,000
Why I'd heard it in the news.

328
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:23,000
But then this, you know, he had been traveling around the country him and H. Rat Brown.

329
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:26,000
And then, you know, wow, he's coming to Seattle.

330
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:29,000
So, I made sure I was here.

331
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:36,000
And that really changed that, that's just like blew us into another direction, you know.

332
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:41,000
You really start thinking about press all these things are going on in America, you know.

333
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:45,000
The riot in, or Los Angeles in 1965.

334
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:46,000
Right.

335
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:51,000
And, you know, the continuous riots after that every summer.

336
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:55,000
And the whole civil rights movement and everything that's going on.

337
00:33:55,000 --> 00:33:59,000
Not to mention that John F. Kennedy had been assassinated.

338
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:05,000
And as was my father cried when that happened when he was assassinated.

339
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:17,000
And, you know, really, what's devastating to the black community because the first time we had a president at that really stood up and was going to support the black people was doing.

340
00:34:17,000 --> 00:34:22,000
So, was his picture up in there in their home?

341
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:26,000
Yeah, I'm sure that, yeah, they had some kind of pictures somewhere.

342
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:32,000
They had, you see, I'm kind of picture.

343
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:39,000
Well, there was artwork on the one with some of my father's artwork and other artwork.

344
00:34:39,000 --> 00:34:47,000
And there was a bus to Beethoven who we later found out was, you know, was black.

345
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:53,000
So, well, we did listen to a lot of Paul Robison.

346
00:34:53,000 --> 00:35:04,000
Paul Robison, what's his name and other Harlem, that Congressman.

347
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:05,000
Oh, power.

348
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:08,000
Yeah, yeah.

349
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:14,000
And records of Martin Luther King.

350
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:20,000
And we listened to a lot of opera, a lot of musicals, a lot of classical music, a lot of jazz.

351
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:24,000
You know, there was music. It was a big part of our family.

352
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:31,000
You know, it was always being played in the house.

353
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:35,000
So, let me see.

354
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:38,000
Yeah, yeah.

355
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:41,000
So, after, after, after, stokely, that's it.

356
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:44,000
You know, I'm all fired up.

357
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:53,000
So, I met my job one day and I have, I have my Ray Bans sunglasses on and I'm wearing them on the job.

358
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:56,000
And my afros getting bigger.

359
00:35:57,000 --> 00:36:08,000
And I worked on this line, this kind of, it was a conveyor belt and everybody, you know, had to put dishes on the trays.

360
00:36:08,000 --> 00:36:19,000
And I had to call them out, you know, what was, it was, you know, sugar-free or whatever type of diet it was.

361
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:24,000
And I messed up a couple of times as I had my son, Razzlebone.

362
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:27,000
And so, the supervisor tells me to take my sunglasses off.

363
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:39,000
Oh, why did she tell me that? I just blew up and I lit into her with all these profanities and walked off my job.

364
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:44,000
I had that job for about three years.

365
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:51,000
And so, now, you know, I don't have a job. I'm not a school. I'm hanging out with my friends.

366
00:36:52,000 --> 00:36:54,000
My mother tells me, you know, I got to do something.

367
00:36:54,000 --> 00:37:09,000
So, I found a little part-time job working with a poverty program that was going around doing these racially racial skits.

368
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:17,000
And so, we're going like the schools and the programs and the different places and, you know, we play these different roles.

369
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:26,000
And then from that, I met this guy who was a playwright named Aaron Dumas and he had written a play.

370
00:37:26,000 --> 00:37:31,000
And so, he asked me to be in his play. It's called General's Coo.

371
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:43,000
It was about a craze. It was about a black army that has raised up and they marched on the capital and they started taking over the country.

372
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:51,000
And they take over the White House and the General gets crazy and I'm his rational son.

373
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:55,000
And we play this play all over in coffee houses. Where they had coffee houses.

374
00:37:55,000 --> 00:37:59,000
Where they still got coffee houses, but they were bigger than there.

375
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:04,000
Coffee houses and, you know, in schools, we were doing this play.

376
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:07,000
And I really started getting into it, you know.

377
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:13,000
So, then after that, we finished with that, I got into another play called Tom Jones.

378
00:38:13,000 --> 00:38:18,000
And so, I'm also writing poetry. I'm also writing a lot of poetry.

379
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:26,000
You know, I'm getting into the theater. I do a poetry reading at the Lynx Fine Arts program.

380
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:30,000
I went to scholarship, $500 scholarship.

381
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:37,000
And I meet this, I hear about this program from this Jewish woman named Mrs. Richmond.

382
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:46,000
I went to school with her daughter. She works with the Urban League and they started up this college program to help blacks get into the University of Washington.

383
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:51,000
And they help get them jobs and they do all this stuff to get advisors form and all these things.

384
00:38:51,000 --> 00:38:59,000
So, man, I took my SAT test and I did good on it. And September, I was at the University of Washington.

385
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:03,000
And now I'm a student there.

386
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:11,000
And now the movement all around us is really catching steam.

387
00:39:11,000 --> 00:39:22,000
So, I get involved with some other black students there and we start the first black student union at the University of Washington.

388
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:31,000
So, we start the black student union and so all of us black students are meeting in the hub.

389
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:36,000
And, you know, Ron Dellum is coming up from Oakland and other organizers from San Francisco State.

390
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:39,000
Because they are, I started a big take over San Francisco State.

391
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:45,000
And so, then we helped to form a PSU in Garfield High School.

392
00:39:45,000 --> 00:39:50,000
And so, you want to say a little bit about that?

393
00:39:50,000 --> 00:39:52,000
Hi, honey.

394
00:39:52,000 --> 00:39:57,000
So, ooh.

395
00:39:57,000 --> 00:39:58,000
Who is this?

396
00:39:58,000 --> 00:40:02,000
This is Telia, my granddaughter.

397
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:06,000
Well, you're now in the record of a wide-breed company.

398
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:17,000
So, anyway, so in our activity, we're getting politicized constantly.

399
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:26,000
You know, and I remember hearing about this organization in Oakland called the Black Panther Party that marks on the Capitol in Sacramento.

400
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:38,000
This was, I believe, in the summer of 1967, I believe it was before I even started school.

401
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:47,000
And so, anyway, you know, going through the PSU, we decided to have this demonstration in Franklin High School.

402
00:40:47,000 --> 00:40:49,000
Because there's a racial incident that occurred there.

403
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:58,000
Plus, they don't have any black, any black or Asian staff on the school set.

404
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:03,000
So, we've had them.

405
00:41:03,000 --> 00:41:04,000
Okay.

406
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:07,000
So, we can go on.

407
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:09,000
Okay, so, Franklin High School.

408
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:10,000
Yeah, so we go to Franklin High School.

409
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:11,000
We march on the school.

410
00:41:11,000 --> 00:41:13,000
We march into the office.

411
00:41:13,000 --> 00:41:15,000
Principal won't meet with us.

412
00:41:15,000 --> 00:41:18,000
So, we march into his office and we're yelling and chanting it.

413
00:41:18,000 --> 00:41:19,000
What was he saying?

414
00:41:19,000 --> 00:41:20,000
Saying our chant.

415
00:41:20,000 --> 00:41:22,000
Oh, it was the set of hiring a black staff.

416
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:23,000
Yeah.

417
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:29,000
And the incident that happened with the black student and the white student, they got in the fight.

418
00:41:29,000 --> 00:41:30,000
The black student got kicked out.

419
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:33,000
The white student remained in school.

420
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:37,000
So, we wanted to address those two issues.

421
00:41:37,000 --> 00:41:39,000
But he refused to meet with us.

422
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:43,000
And we marched into his office and we're yelling our chant.

423
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:45,000
So, he decides to leave the school.

424
00:41:45,000 --> 00:41:48,000
And he tells us the staff to go home.

425
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:50,000
And so, the students are there.

426
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:55,000
And so, we get the students into the auditorium and we have a big rally.

427
00:41:55,000 --> 00:42:01,000
And so, afterwards, we're feeling really like, yeah, man, we did something here.

428
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:03,000
We took over the school.

429
00:42:03,000 --> 00:42:05,000
We ran them out of there.

430
00:42:05,000 --> 00:42:07,000
So, we're feeling really good.

431
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:12,000
A week later, I get arrested from my home.

432
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:16,000
And along with other leaders of the demonstration.

433
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:18,000
And we're in the King County jail.

434
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:19,000
Charged with it.

435
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:22,000
Unlawful assembly.

436
00:42:22,000 --> 00:42:26,000
The day is April 4th, 1968.

437
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:30,000
And Walter Concrite comes on announces Margaret the King is assassinated.

438
00:42:31,000 --> 00:42:33,000
So, this was...

439
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:35,000
Yeah, we're in jail.

440
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:42,000
And then the riots are breaking out all across the country, even in Seattle.

441
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:44,000
And young people are going crazy.

442
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:48,000
And we want to be out there going crazy, but we can't.

443
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:53,000
So, I remember that evening going back to my bulk.

444
00:42:54,000 --> 00:43:02,000
And saying to myself that they killed Margaret the King, a man of peace.

445
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:07,000
That now is time for something else.

446
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:13,000
And I decided that my picket sign was going to be replaced by a gun.

447
00:43:13,000 --> 00:43:17,000
We had already had been doing some organizing with SNCC.

448
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:22,000
And we had met this guy named Brutu Man, who we're all going over there

449
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:23,000
to his house meeting.

450
00:43:23,000 --> 00:43:25,000
And he had some guns over there.

451
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:31,000
And so, the idea had already been implanted in our heads, along with Stoke and Carmichael.

452
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:36,000
And others that armed violence was what was needed.

453
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:41,000
And did you look at in terms of self-defense or...

454
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:43,000
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

455
00:43:43,000 --> 00:43:45,000
Well, whatever.

456
00:43:45,000 --> 00:43:47,000
You know, whatever.

457
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:49,000
However, we...

458
00:43:49,000 --> 00:43:52,000
I don't even think we had really even thought about it.

459
00:43:52,000 --> 00:43:55,000
You know, we didn't know what we were going to do with the guns.

460
00:43:55,000 --> 00:44:04,000
But it probably was more about self-defense, because we had seen a lot of police brutality that had been taking place.

461
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:12,000
So, you know, then in the backdrop you had, you know, Chagavera and Fidel Castro,

462
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:17,000
and then Marston, Havana, and the movie had just came out about Chagavera.

463
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:22,000
And you had the revolutionary movements that were taking place throughout South America,

464
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:27,000
Chile, Argentina, Brazil, and then as well as in Africa.

465
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:33,000
So, you know, all over the world, actually, you had this kind of uprising of young people,

466
00:44:33,000 --> 00:44:39,000
you know, Europe and France, London, you know, even in India.

467
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:49,000
So, then you had the whole hippie movement, and the movement against the anti-war movement.

468
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:56,000
So, you know, it just seemed like, okay, America is just, you know, you're made to explode.

469
00:44:56,000 --> 00:44:59,000
You know, people want to change.

470
00:44:59,000 --> 00:45:06,000
And so, we finally got out of jail, and then I was ended up...

471
00:45:06,000 --> 00:45:11,000
We went down to the Black Student Union Conference in San Francisco,

472
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:16,000
and while we were down there, we...

473
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:22,000
Bobby heard that Bobby sealed the leader of the Black Panther Party was coming to do the keynote address.

474
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:29,000
So, but we also heard that there was a funeral of this Panther who had been killed.

475
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:34,000
His name was Little Bobby Hutton. He was known as Little Bobby Hutton.

476
00:45:34,000 --> 00:45:40,000
So, we went over to the funeral, and we had stopped and got some burrays before we went over there.

477
00:45:40,000 --> 00:45:45,000
And we saw Marlon Brando standing out front with the Black...

478
00:45:45,000 --> 00:45:48,000
...and the Jacket on the Black Burray talking with Bobby Seal.

479
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:50,000
We're going to the church.

480
00:45:50,000 --> 00:45:52,000
Why did you stop to get the burrays?

481
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:58,000
Because that's what the Panthers wore, and we wanted to fit in, you know, we wanted to fit in.

482
00:45:58,000 --> 00:46:03,000
And show solidarity.

483
00:46:03,000 --> 00:46:08,000
And so, we...

484
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:12,000
We, you know, go in and see the body of Little Bobby Hutton.

485
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:19,000
It's a very emotional setting. His mother answered, wailing and crying and reaching out to his body.

486
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:23,000
And these Panthers are standing around the walls, you know, with their hands.

487
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:27,000
Arms folded, you know, looking very serious.

488
00:46:27,000 --> 00:46:29,000
What were the circumstances of this?

489
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:35,000
He was, you know, it was because of Martin Luther King's death, you know.

490
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:42,000
And that there were some Panthers that wanted to take revenge, and they went out on the street.

491
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:50,000
And it wasn't something that was okay by the leadership, but it was some people that decided they wanted to do this on their own.

492
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:53,000
One of them was a leader in the party.

493
00:46:53,000 --> 00:46:57,000
It was Elders Cleveland, David, L.U. too, as well.

494
00:46:57,000 --> 00:47:02,000
Elders Huey and Bobby were in jail at the time.

495
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:05,000
Otherwise, they wouldn't allow this thing to happen.

496
00:47:05,000 --> 00:47:09,000
So, they decided to go out on the street to, you know, try to do something.

497
00:47:09,000 --> 00:47:16,000
They... getting a confrontation with some police to shoot out and soothe Little Bobby Hutton.

498
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:18,000
They would just leave her right into this abandoned house.

499
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:22,000
It's surrounded by police. They start shooting into the house.

500
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:26,000
You know, this goes on for, you know, 20, 30, 40 minutes to your gas.

501
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:31,000
And finally, you know, they have to surrender.

502
00:47:31,000 --> 00:47:38,000
Little Bobby Hutton throws his rifle out the door, and they come out with their hands up.

503
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:42,000
Little Bobby Hutton is told to run towards a police car.

504
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:46,000
And he does, and they shoot him.

505
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:50,000
And you know, shoot him about 20, 25 times, you know.

506
00:47:51,000 --> 00:47:57,000
And not only was Bobby Hutton killed, but Elders Peever was wounded.

507
00:47:57,000 --> 00:48:02,000
And also put in jail, because he's an ex-fellon now.

508
00:48:02,000 --> 00:48:06,000
And they're going to send him back to San Quentin.

509
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:11,000
David Hear you at the National Captain is also arrested.

510
00:48:11,000 --> 00:48:16,000
And there's 18 other Panthers that are all arrested.

511
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:20,000
And another Panther that is wounded.

512
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:24,000
And these were early Panthers. These were early people.

513
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:28,000
And so now they're taken off the streets.

514
00:48:28,000 --> 00:48:32,000
What's that got to say? Sound like an effort to just cut the Panther.

515
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:37,000
Yeah, it really had a devastating effect.

516
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:41,000
So that's what happened with Little Bobby Hutton.

517
00:48:41,000 --> 00:48:44,000
And so Bobby Seale comes over later on that evening,

518
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:46,000
who knows he's very emotional.

519
00:48:46,000 --> 00:48:52,000
He comes with Kathleen Cleaver and one of the wounded Panthers.

520
00:48:52,000 --> 00:48:58,000
And he gives a speech that is very powerful, very emotionally charged.

521
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:02,000
And my brother and I, after the speech, along with Anthony,

522
00:49:02,000 --> 00:49:05,000
where we make a B-line to where he's at.

523
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:10,000
And we tell him we want a Black Panther Party chapter in Seattle.

524
00:49:10,000 --> 00:49:11,000
And so we played her.

525
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:13,000
She flies to Seattle.

526
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:16,000
Along with George Murray, the Minister of Education,

527
00:49:16,000 --> 00:49:20,000
who was also a professor at San Francisco State College.

528
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:23,000
And was very much behind the big student strike they had there

529
00:49:23,000 --> 00:49:26,000
for Black Studies program.

530
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:30,000
And how radical was the Black Student Union?

531
00:49:30,000 --> 00:49:35,000
I'm going to construct as they invited him to be the keynote.

532
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:38,000
Yeah. Well, the thing is,

533
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:43,000
is that the Black Panther Party was such a powerful force

534
00:49:43,000 --> 00:49:50,000
in the Bay Area and influencing force and a growing force

535
00:49:50,000 --> 00:49:53,000
that you couldn't help but want to invite them.

536
00:49:53,000 --> 00:49:57,000
Plus, there were people, and there were people at San Francisco State

537
00:49:57,000 --> 00:49:59,000
who were in the Black Panther Party.

538
00:49:59,000 --> 00:50:02,000
And there were a lot of the people who in the BSU

539
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:05,000
who associated and worked with the Black Panther Party.

540
00:50:05,000 --> 00:50:08,000
You know, you had Emory Douglas, who was a Minister of Culture

541
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:10,000
of the Black Panther Party. He was a student there.

542
00:50:10,000 --> 00:50:12,000
You know, George Murray, the Minister of Education,

543
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:14,000
was a professor there.

544
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:18,000
So that whole student strike,

545
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:22,000
the Black Panther Party had was one of the most key elements

546
00:50:22,000 --> 00:50:24,000
in making that happen.

547
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:29,000
So Bobby Seal comes to Seattle with George Murray.

548
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:33,000
And there's about 20 people who all meet at my mother's house,

549
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:38,000
my parents' house. We meet over a two or three day period.

550
00:50:38,000 --> 00:50:43,000
And, you know, a couple of people bring their guns to the meeting.

551
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:50,000
And so he tells us what you need to be in the Black Panther Party.

552
00:50:50,000 --> 00:50:53,000
You know, he starts off that you need to have two weapons

553
00:50:53,000 --> 00:50:55,000
and two thousand rounds ammunition.

554
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:58,000
And he also gives us a book, that's a 25 books,

555
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:00,000
that we're told we have to read.

556
00:51:00,000 --> 00:51:03,000
And we have to read, study two hours a day

557
00:51:03,000 --> 00:51:06,000
and have a little credit to casing class twice a week.

558
00:51:06,000 --> 00:51:10,000
And he's on his way to the East Coast

559
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:13,000
to organize other chapters and branches.

560
00:51:13,000 --> 00:51:15,000
He asked me to go with him.

561
00:51:15,000 --> 00:51:17,000
But I wasn't ready to go.

562
00:51:17,000 --> 00:51:21,000
You know, in the meeting he asked who's going to be the captain.

563
00:51:21,000 --> 00:51:27,000
And it was, I was a dead thing as the captain.

564
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:29,000
So we started developing.

565
00:51:29,000 --> 00:51:31,000
Were you up for that role or were you voted into it?

566
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:32,000
Or how was it you were?

567
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:33,000
I was kind of voted into it.

568
00:51:33,000 --> 00:51:35,000
You know, everybody stopped pointing at me.

569
00:51:35,000 --> 00:51:38,000
I don't know why, but they did.

570
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:39,000
So...

571
00:51:39,000 --> 00:51:42,000
And you're 19 years old?

572
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:44,000
Yeah, 19.

573
00:51:44,000 --> 00:51:46,000
And still a student that you do.

574
00:51:46,000 --> 00:51:49,000
So a week later, I'm called to Oakland.

575
00:51:49,000 --> 00:51:51,000
I'm called by the Civil College of Intelligence.

576
00:51:51,000 --> 00:51:52,000
It has to come down.

577
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:54,000
It was my first flight on the airplane.

578
00:51:54,000 --> 00:51:57,000
I had my black pants uniform on.

579
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:03,000
And I'm nervous about how I'm going to be accepted by these guys.

580
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:06,000
So at that point, what is the black pants uniform?

581
00:52:06,000 --> 00:52:17,000
It's a black leather jacket, powder blue shirt with the black tie, black pants, black beret, and black shoes.

582
00:52:17,000 --> 00:52:20,000
Or black combat boots.

583
00:52:20,000 --> 00:52:22,000
And so that was a uniform.

584
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:24,000
A official uniform of the black pants, probably.

585
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:27,000
And that's part of the members.

586
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:30,000
We cried to wear most of the time.

587
00:52:30,000 --> 00:52:36,000
And so, okay, I'm picked up for the airport by two pantas, Robert Bay,

588
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:46,000
who is a Vietnam veteran, along with Tommy Jones, who is also a veteran from the Navy.

589
00:52:46,000 --> 00:52:50,000
And he's from Tacoma, Washington.

590
00:52:50,000 --> 00:52:52,000
Robert Bay's a captain.

591
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:54,000
So I'm over to the office.

592
00:52:54,000 --> 00:52:59,000
I meet the National Secretary.

593
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:04,000
And she tells me that Bobby Seal catch up with me in a couple of days.

594
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:06,000
And so I'm staying with Landon and Randy.

595
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:08,000
I'm staying with Tommy Jones.

596
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:14,000
But Robert Bay takes me to his house to meet Landon and Randy Williams, who are also captains.

597
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:20,000
They are Vietnam's Special Forces veterans.

598
00:53:20,000 --> 00:53:26,000
And the first thing that they start wanting to show me was their weaponry.

599
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:29,000
And they each have their own armament in their rooms.

600
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:32,000
And they have bullet loading equipment.

601
00:53:32,000 --> 00:53:38,000
And they're showing me their weapons and their handguns.

602
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:48,000
And so it's becoming clear that I'm in a serious organization with people that are really serious about what they're doing.

603
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:51,000
Did you handle the weaponry at that point in your life?

604
00:53:51,000 --> 00:53:54,000
Yeah, growing up, we all had BB guns.

605
00:53:54,000 --> 00:53:56,000
And we had 22s.

606
00:53:56,000 --> 00:53:59,000
And we went hunting with 22s.

607
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:05,000
So yeah, and I'd handled a weapon at Voodoo Man's house.

608
00:54:05,000 --> 00:54:13,000
And we had friends who did a lot of hunting.

609
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:18,000
And so they always had gun racks at their house.

610
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:26,000
And so guns were not foreign at all to me or us.

611
00:54:26,000 --> 00:54:34,000
So I go to visit Huey and Jail.

612
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:37,000
That's one of the things I have to do is visit him.

613
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:42,000
I go out and sell papers with some Black Panther Party members.

614
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:46,000
And then I spent some time with Bobby Seale, traveling from Maricopa,

615
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:48,000
other meeting with BSU members.

616
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:53,000
And then we end up in San Francisco at a Central Committee meeting.

617
00:54:53,000 --> 00:55:06,000
And at that meeting is Stokeley Carmichael, Don Cox, the Field Marshal of the Black Panther Party.

618
00:55:06,000 --> 00:55:10,000
They will heal you to the National Captain.

619
00:55:10,000 --> 00:55:17,000
And some other people, some other captains of the Black Panther.

620
00:55:17,000 --> 00:55:21,000
And these guys are older guys.

621
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:27,000
And so I'm introduced as a new captain.

622
00:55:27,000 --> 00:55:35,000
And then the next day I'm with Robert Bayland and in Randy and we're at the house.

623
00:55:35,000 --> 00:55:41,000
We're drinking some, what is called, bitter dog, which was a street drink,

624
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:44,000
which is dark pork wine for a little bit out.

625
00:55:44,000 --> 00:55:46,000
And you put some lemon juice in there.

626
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:48,000
You shake it out. It was pretty potent drink.

627
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:51,000
And later became known as Panther Piss.

628
00:55:51,000 --> 00:55:54,000
It was dubbed Panther Piss. So we're drinking that.

629
00:55:54,000 --> 00:56:00,000
We're smoking some brother Rugi, which is the code name for marijuana.

630
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:07,000
And Landon didn't drink or smoke weed, so he's in the front room watching TV.

631
00:56:07,000 --> 00:56:14,000
So I'm getting it feeling no more comfortable and you know, loosening up and everything.

632
00:56:15,000 --> 00:56:18,000
And suddenly we're here, a loud bang.

633
00:56:18,000 --> 00:56:25,000
And we run into the living room and Landon is there with this 44 Magnum in his hand.

634
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:27,000
And Robert Bay says, man, what'd you do?

635
00:56:27,000 --> 00:56:29,000
Man, why'd you shoot the TV out?

636
00:56:29,000 --> 00:56:32,000
He said, I was tired of watching the Cowboys and Indians.

637
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:38,000
And the Indians always get killed. I shot the TV out.

638
00:56:38,000 --> 00:56:42,000
And later on, right after that, we're going on to Seville Street in West Oakland.

639
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:47,000
We get something to eat.

640
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:55,000
And me and another young Panther named Orlando Harris, who was in Sacramento.

641
00:56:55,000 --> 00:57:01,000
When they took the arm delegation, he's only 16 years old.

642
00:57:01,000 --> 00:57:04,000
I think he was 15 when he went to Sacramento.

643
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:11,000
And he's very prominent in that film, holding an M1 car being with the toothpick in his mouth.

644
00:57:12,000 --> 00:57:18,000
So me and him go out and we're smoking cigarettes and a car drives by police car.

645
00:57:18,000 --> 00:57:20,000
He starts yelling at it.

646
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:22,000
Pig, you damn pig, you rest up at that stuff.

647
00:57:22,000 --> 00:57:25,000
It's a cussing at the pig and he's just going off.

648
00:57:25,000 --> 00:57:28,000
So I join in and I'm doing it too.

649
00:57:28,000 --> 00:57:34,000
And this is only maybe two weeks after Little Bobby Hutton had been killed.

650
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:40,000
And there's a lot of tension, a lot of tension between the police department and the Black Panther Party.

651
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:45,000
And pretty soon the police goes around, he comes back and he calls for reinforcements.

652
00:57:45,000 --> 00:57:48,000
More police start driving up on the scene.

653
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:54,000
The Robert Bay landing in a Randy come out in time with Jones, they come out.

654
00:57:54,000 --> 00:58:00,000
And then people are actually running home and closing their stores and saying,

655
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:03,000
I'm getting out of here, it's going to be a shootout.

656
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:08,000
And this is the same corner that Huey Newton had his shootout,

657
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:12,000
he was wounded and two police were one was killed, one was wounded.

658
00:58:12,000 --> 00:58:15,000
Same corner, seventh and wood.

659
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:20,000
So people are running, there's going to be, and people are pretty soon, the street is deserted almost.

660
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:27,000
And the prostitutes are the only ones that they're out there saying they're going to stay here and help see what happened to the panthers.

661
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:32,000
And I just remember Robert Bay comes out, he says spread out.

662
00:58:32,000 --> 00:58:34,000
You know, he says spread out in this deep voice.

663
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:39,000
So we all spread out, the police are all bunched together.

664
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:41,000
The police have their hands on their guns.

665
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:45,000
And without so it's not to give them a bunch of targets.

666
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:50,000
Exactly, right. So we spread out, police, they don't spread out, they're all bunches up.

667
00:58:50,000 --> 00:58:53,000
They're showing a lot more fear than we are.

668
00:58:53,000 --> 00:58:56,000
They got their hands on their guns, we have our hands on our guns.

669
00:58:56,000 --> 00:59:03,000
I had just been given a 9 millimeter automatic the day before.

670
00:59:03,000 --> 00:59:06,000
And so we're all armed.

671
00:59:06,000 --> 00:59:11,000
And I remember seeing a pretty soon the streets deserted.

672
00:59:11,000 --> 00:59:16,000
So I'm thinking, oh shit man, what have I got myself into?

673
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:20,000
So I see this young black guy, he's got a bag of groceries.

674
00:59:20,000 --> 00:59:24,000
And I'm sending myself, I wish he would stay here and help us.

675
00:59:24,000 --> 00:59:30,000
And our eyes meet, and he looks at me and he says, man I would stay here and help you, but I got to get home.

676
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:33,000
And then he's gone.

677
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:39,000
And so now the police, there's a lieutenant out front of the police.

678
00:59:39,000 --> 00:59:43,000
And he's looking at Landon, because Landon's out front of us.

679
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:47,000
And he's got his hand on his gun, he said, I'm going to search you.

680
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:50,000
And Landon says, no you're not going to search me.

681
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:53,000
And Landon, he starts walking towards Landon.

682
00:59:53,000 --> 00:59:55,000
Landon starts backing up.

683
00:59:55,000 --> 00:59:58,000
And I'm thinking shit Landon shot that TV out, shit.

684
00:59:58,000 --> 01:00:01,000
You know what I'm telling him, what he's going to do.

685
01:00:01,000 --> 01:00:07,000
So, and this went on for a few seconds, you know.

686
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:14,000
And it was so much tension, you could have cut it as cliché as it sounds.

687
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:18,000
But suddenly Landon tripped over a garbage can top.

688
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:23,000
He bounces right back up, but the garbage, you can hear the garbage can top reverberating.

689
01:00:23,000 --> 01:00:27,000
And that just like cuts the tension.

690
01:00:27,000 --> 01:00:30,000
Because the next thing, the police turn around.

691
01:00:30,000 --> 01:00:36,000
They don't say a word, they turn around, they get in their cars and they drive off.

692
01:00:36,000 --> 01:00:40,000
So, this was a victory for us.

693
01:00:40,000 --> 01:00:43,000
You know, we stood our ground.

694
01:00:43,000 --> 01:00:49,000
And they chose that this was not a night that they wanted to engage with us.

695
01:00:49,000 --> 01:00:56,000
And so, we gave our guns to the prostitutes because we figured they're going to come back with more reinforcements.

696
01:00:56,000 --> 01:01:00,000
And then finally we left and go home.

697
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:05,000
So, that was my baptism into the Black Panther Party that night.

698
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:14,000
And so, the very next day, they have the Saturday Panther meeting that they have every week at the St. Augustine's Church.

699
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:25,000
And so, panzers are coming from all over the Bay Area, San Mateo, San Jose, Richmond, Relayo, and everywhere.

700
01:01:25,000 --> 01:01:30,000
There's about 125 people in there, you know, men and women.

701
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:32,000
You know, most people have the uniformed on.

702
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:34,000
And it's just electrifying.

703
01:01:34,000 --> 01:01:36,000
And Bob Sierge gets up and he talks.

704
01:01:36,000 --> 01:01:38,000
And he talks about the 10-point program.

705
01:01:38,000 --> 01:01:41,000
We got to know the 10-point program and recite it.

706
01:01:41,000 --> 01:01:43,000
And he introduces me.

707
01:01:43,000 --> 01:01:47,000
And I met you, Duce, as a first captain of the Seattle Chapter.

708
01:01:47,000 --> 01:01:50,000
First office outside of the state of California.

709
01:01:50,000 --> 01:01:55,000
And so, after the meeting, you know, everybody's greeting me.

710
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:59,000
And, you know, I feel really like, you know, this is my new family.

711
01:01:59,000 --> 01:02:03,000
And so, I leave with Robert Bay and Tommy Jones.

712
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:05,000
We go back to the house.

713
01:02:05,000 --> 01:02:08,000
And when we get to the house, the phone rings.

714
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:10,000
Robert Bay runs and grabs the answer to the phone.

715
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:13,000
He said, yeah, he slammed the phone down.

716
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:14,000
He runs to his room.

717
01:02:14,000 --> 01:02:15,000
He grabs two rifles.

718
01:02:15,000 --> 01:02:18,000
He hands me one at a box of ammo.

719
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:21,000
And he says, the vampen on the camera is at the church.

720
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:25,000
So, we're jumping this car and he's speeding going about 50,

721
01:02:25,000 --> 01:02:27,000
60 miles an hour down Gro street.

722
01:02:27,000 --> 01:02:30,000
And they asked me if I know how to load the weapon.

723
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:33,000
And I said, yeah, I mean, I'd never seen that 40.

724
01:02:33,000 --> 01:02:35,000
It was a 44-magnum car being.

725
01:02:35,000 --> 01:02:37,000
But I figured out how to load it.

726
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:38,000
You know, so I load it.

727
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:40,000
And I'm saying, damn, here we go again.

728
01:02:40,000 --> 01:02:42,000
So, we get down to the church.

729
01:02:42,000 --> 01:02:44,000
There's nobody there.

730
01:02:44,000 --> 01:02:49,000
And so, I don't know what happened or what the call was,

731
01:02:49,000 --> 01:02:52,000
or if they left, but nobody's there.

732
01:02:52,000 --> 01:02:55,000
So, we're relieved and nobody's there.

733
01:02:55,000 --> 01:02:56,000
So, we're going back.

734
01:02:56,000 --> 01:02:59,000
The next day, I'm on a flight back to Seattle.

735
01:02:59,000 --> 01:03:04,000
So, I know what it is about to be in the Black Panther Party.

736
01:03:04,000 --> 01:03:11,000
And so, I began, we began organizing the Seattle chapter.

737
01:03:11,000 --> 01:03:15,000
And we opened up our first office and get our phones.

738
01:03:15,000 --> 01:03:20,000
And take over 300 applications in over a month,

739
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:23,000
period of time, people wanting to join the Black Panther Party.

740
01:03:23,000 --> 01:03:24,000
And...

741
01:03:24,000 --> 01:03:27,000
That's going to say, I mean, they had to have the hot adrenaline

742
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:29,000
of these kind of things.

743
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:30,000
Yeah.

744
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:32,000
Yeah, well, that was just the beginning.

745
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:34,000
And that was just the beginning.

746
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:35,000
That was just the beginning.

747
01:03:35,000 --> 01:03:38,000
You know, that was, oh my God.

748
01:03:38,000 --> 01:03:42,000
So, anyway, you know, we open up our office.

749
01:03:42,000 --> 01:03:46,000
We, you know, we've got all these young people and older people,

750
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:49,000
Vietnam, Bets, and the joining of everybody.

751
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:51,000
And we're carrying our guns around.

752
01:03:51,000 --> 01:03:55,000
We're because it's not illegal to carry a gun down the street.

753
01:03:55,000 --> 01:03:59,000
So, we're carrying our rifles, our shotguns, with us everywhere we go,

754
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:02,000
every up and down street in the cars.

755
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:04,000
These are all legally acquired guns.

756
01:04:04,000 --> 01:04:05,000
They're legally acquired.

757
01:04:05,000 --> 01:04:08,000
Well, I won't say they're all legally acquired.

758
01:04:08,000 --> 01:04:11,000
They definitely weren't all legally acquired.

759
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:12,000
But they were legal guns.

760
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:14,000
They were automatic weapons.

761
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:15,000
Okay.

762
01:04:15,000 --> 01:04:17,000
So, you know, then...

763
01:04:17,000 --> 01:04:19,000
And to the police that were hassled you over?

764
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:20,000
Oh, yeah.

765
01:04:20,000 --> 01:04:23,000
We're having confrontations continuously, you know,

766
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:25,000
as continuous confrontations.

767
01:04:25,000 --> 01:04:29,000
And we started getting calls from the community

768
01:04:29,000 --> 01:04:33,000
and we started getting domestic violent calls,

769
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:37,000
landlord disputes, problems with the police.

770
01:04:37,000 --> 01:04:40,000
And, you know, we're trying to answer these calls.

771
01:04:40,000 --> 01:04:44,000
And, you know, the domestic violence calls,

772
01:04:44,000 --> 01:04:46,000
we'll send some armed pantas over there.

773
01:04:46,000 --> 01:04:51,000
And they would, you know, stop that domestic violence that's going on.

774
01:04:51,000 --> 01:04:54,000
It was really empowering.

775
01:04:54,000 --> 01:04:58,000
And for the first time, the community had somebody they could call.

776
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:00,000
You know, for all kinds of problems.

777
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:04,000
And for the first time, they could just pick the phone up and say,

778
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:06,000
you know, hey, I got this problem.

779
01:05:06,000 --> 01:05:07,000
I got that problem.

780
01:05:07,000 --> 01:05:10,000
Will you send some people over here to help me?

781
01:05:10,000 --> 01:05:12,000
You know, there was an incident where...

782
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:15,000
In America, we're talking about supposed to be the police.

783
01:05:15,000 --> 01:05:17,000
But was that not the case?

784
01:05:17,000 --> 01:05:19,000
Oh, no, it wasn't the case.

785
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:22,000
In Seattle or anywhere else, you know.

786
01:05:22,000 --> 01:05:28,000
So, we now were filling that role.

787
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:33,000
So, there was a landlord incident where the landlord had taken the door off

788
01:05:33,000 --> 01:05:36,000
of a hench of a woman who had seven kids.

789
01:05:36,000 --> 01:05:39,000
And we sent some pantas to the house.

790
01:05:39,000 --> 01:05:44,000
And they got the door and carried it down the street

791
01:05:44,000 --> 01:05:49,000
and put it back on the woman's... on the henches.

792
01:05:52,000 --> 01:05:55,000
So, we started getting calls from this high school.

793
01:05:55,000 --> 01:06:00,000
We had a senior in week reports to Bobby Seal and we talked on the phone.

794
01:06:00,000 --> 01:06:05,000
He told me, said, Dixon, you guys are going out on too many of these community calls

795
01:06:05,000 --> 01:06:08,000
because the community likes to take advantage of you.

796
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:12,000
So, I want you to, you know, cut back on that.

797
01:06:12,000 --> 01:06:14,000
What was your response to?

798
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:16,000
Right on, right on Chairman.

799
01:06:16,000 --> 01:06:19,000
Right on Chairman Bobby, you know.

800
01:06:19,000 --> 01:06:23,000
You know, we... you had to follow orders and all your actions.

801
01:06:23,000 --> 01:06:28,000
That was one of the models of the Black Panther Party, all the orders and all your actions.

802
01:06:28,000 --> 01:06:31,000
Now, we all doing your reading service.

803
01:06:31,000 --> 01:06:33,000
We have a political education class.

804
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:35,000
We're having our red book.

805
01:06:35,000 --> 01:06:37,000
You know, we studied the red book.

806
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:43,000
Chairman Miles Red books because it had a lot of things in there that were just basic common things.

807
01:06:43,000 --> 01:06:47,000
You know, the three models and seven rules.

808
01:06:47,000 --> 01:06:51,000
And just, you know, like you don't take anything from the people of the mass.

809
01:06:51,000 --> 01:06:56,000
You turn everything, you borrow, you know, you fight against liberalism.

810
01:06:56,000 --> 01:07:01,000
Criticism, constructive criticism and self-criticism.

811
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:11,000
And just all very basic things to help us, you know, with the day-to-day struggles and between ourselves and what we had to do.

812
01:07:11,000 --> 01:07:15,000
As well as, you know, our political education class where we were, you know,

813
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:22,000
usually read out of the newspaper and discussed things that was in the Black Panther newspaper.

814
01:07:22,000 --> 01:07:29,000
And so, you know, the Black Panther Party is spreading all across the country around this time.

815
01:07:29,000 --> 01:07:40,000
And L.A. chapter is really catching a lot of, you know, three Panthers of Killed and L.A. and the Summer of 1968.

816
01:07:40,000 --> 01:07:45,000
So, you read out some pretty heavy stuff.

817
01:07:45,000 --> 01:07:52,000
Yeah, France for non-Bridge, other earths, Black Sea and White Mass, Black Rage and other things.

818
01:07:52,000 --> 01:07:59,000
I mean, you know, even before that, we were already reading heavy stuff, you know, in college and even in high school.

819
01:07:59,000 --> 01:08:04,000
We're, because there was a lot of Black writers who were writing a lot of, there was James Baldwin.

820
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:09,000
We always read a lot of James Baldwin, Richard Wright and many, many others.

821
01:08:09,000 --> 01:08:14,000
You know, we were, we really read a lot even before we got into the party.

822
01:08:14,000 --> 01:08:16,000
We were reading all these books.

823
01:08:16,000 --> 01:08:22,000
But the folks that were being, that were applying to the membership and that were joining you.

824
01:08:22,000 --> 01:08:28,000
Were they, were they down with this kind of reading? Or, you know, this is the whole thing with a lump in full eternity.

825
01:08:28,000 --> 01:08:30,000
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

826
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:32,000
The lump in ready to read?

827
01:08:32,000 --> 01:08:36,000
Well, yeah, yeah. I mean, people had the attempt through little education class.

828
01:08:36,000 --> 01:08:43,000
People had to get the books. And, you know, Bobby Hutton didn't know how to read or write before he joined a party.

829
01:08:43,000 --> 01:08:46,000
And by the time he's 17, he knows how to read and he knows how to write.

830
01:08:46,000 --> 01:08:53,000
Because he's reading these things, you know, that he has to read and, and comrades help him with that as well.

831
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:59,000
So, and then we started getting a lot of college educated, college students that began to join the Black Rage experts.

832
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:05,000
So you got a combination of the lump in full eternity, and you got all these college students that are coming in as well.

833
01:09:05,000 --> 01:09:15,000
So, it was a good combination of the two, you know, coming together.

834
01:09:15,000 --> 01:09:25,000
So, so we started getting calls from this woman on Monday that her son was going to an all white high school.

835
01:09:25,000 --> 01:09:28,000
He got beat up in the Prince of Wood doing thing about it.

836
01:09:28,000 --> 01:09:31,000
So I explained her we couldn't come out there.

837
01:09:31,000 --> 01:09:36,000
So she called back on Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday. Sorry, ma'am, we can't come.

838
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:42,000
She called back on Friday. She was crying towards the end of the school year. White students had bought bats and changed the school.

839
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:46,000
They were beating the kids and threatening the kids. Nobody were doing thing about it.

840
01:09:46,000 --> 01:09:50,000
And so we got another call from another mother, same thing.

841
01:09:50,000 --> 01:10:00,000
And so, when we got that last call, there were about 13 panthers in the office and everybody had their rifle and shotgun.

842
01:10:00,000 --> 01:10:07,000
So I said, okay, let's go. We're going to go. So we get out there. There's 25 policemen there on the side of the building.

843
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:09,000
Already there. Already there.

844
01:10:09,000 --> 01:10:16,000
Well, they might have been called out there because of the disturbance, because of what was going on.

845
01:10:16,000 --> 01:10:17,000
Which hospital?

846
01:10:17,000 --> 01:10:20,000
Rainer Beach.

847
01:10:20,000 --> 01:10:23,000
By this time, school is already out.

848
01:10:23,000 --> 01:10:30,000
So we cross the street. One of the sergeants says, Dixon, you can't take those loaded weapons into the school.

849
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:31,000
They don't know you at this point.

850
01:10:31,000 --> 01:10:35,000
Yeah, they know they know me. They know, you know, they are the comrades.

851
01:10:35,000 --> 01:10:46,000
And so knowing the gun laws and the gun law states it, if a bullet is not in the chamber and you're carrying it, then it is considered unloaded.

852
01:10:46,000 --> 01:10:52,000
So they're not loaded. We go right into the office, into the school.

853
01:10:52,000 --> 01:10:58,000
We see the principal. He sees us. He takes off running. We go back. That's how we get somebody.

854
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:07,000
They go get them and they escort them and sit them down and we tell them, you know, if you don't start protecting these kids, we're going to protect them.

855
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:13,000
And he is visibly shaken and he promises that for an hour, he will protect them.

856
01:11:13,000 --> 01:11:21,000
And so we leave. We back our way across the street. We don't turn our backs to the police because that's one of the things he told me when I went to visit them.

857
01:11:21,000 --> 01:11:24,000
They'll turn you back to the pigs.

858
01:11:24,000 --> 01:11:29,000
We get in our cars and we drive back. They follow us back, but they don't stop us.

859
01:11:29,000 --> 01:11:35,000
And they're trying to come up with some kind of indictment against us, but we didn't do anything illegal.

860
01:11:35,000 --> 01:11:36,000
Right.

861
01:11:36,000 --> 01:11:42,000
Because there's no law at that time against bringing rifle and shotguns into the school.

862
01:11:42,000 --> 01:11:53,000
But that was the first major incident that really marked the emergence of the Seattle chapter.

863
01:11:53,000 --> 01:11:55,000
Okay.

864
01:11:55,000 --> 01:12:01,000
So, I mean, there's a lot of things that happened. I mean, I can't tell you everything.

865
01:12:01,000 --> 01:12:08,000
You know, I would just say that we had some, there were some people who had joined the party for their own personal reasons.

866
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:20,000
And, you know, there were elements that were starting to do robbing banks and robbing stores that were connected to the party.

867
01:12:20,000 --> 01:12:29,000
And, you know, the same thing happened, started happening in Oakland because a lot of these people, we didn't really have a way of providing income for people.

868
01:12:29,000 --> 01:12:38,000
So, a lot of people, but in the Bay Area, just for a lot of people did, what they started, people who were from the lump and they started reverting back to their old tactic.

869
01:12:38,000 --> 01:12:41,000
And the fact that they had a uniform on and a gun.

870
01:12:41,000 --> 01:12:47,000
Because when you give young men a gun and you put a uniform on, they do crazy things.

871
01:12:47,000 --> 01:12:52,000
And this was starting to happen within the party.

872
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:55,000
And then, would you try to control that?

873
01:12:55,000 --> 01:13:03,000
Well, we had, what Huey did was, he, from prison, he gave an order that we had to have a purge.

874
01:13:03,000 --> 01:13:11,000
So, we began to expel these people from the party, you know, and Oakland had a big purge in the Bay Area.

875
01:13:11,000 --> 01:13:14,000
And, in Seattle, we had a big purge here as two.

876
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:21,000
And it really almost destroyed the party. There were two people that lost their lives behind this activity that was taking place.

877
01:13:21,000 --> 01:13:28,000
It really damaged our credibility in the media, in the community.

878
01:13:28,000 --> 01:13:35,000
And, you know, even people left because of that.

879
01:13:35,000 --> 01:13:39,000
I know, particularly in Seattle, they were bombing instance.

880
01:13:39,000 --> 01:13:40,000
Right, fire bomb.

881
01:13:40,000 --> 01:13:44,000
Yeah, well, that was separate. That was separate from incident.

882
01:13:44,000 --> 01:13:54,000
And that was separate because in July, after our return from New York was Bobby Seal and Elders Cleaver and Emory Douglas,

883
01:13:54,000 --> 01:14:10,000
we went to the UN for the purpose of getting the UN to intervene in the trial of Huey Newton and intervene on the genocidal practices of the US against the Black community.

884
01:14:10,000 --> 01:14:20,000
And so, it was a whole plan that the party had developed by going into the UN and having Black Panther Party members standing with free Huey flags

885
01:14:20,000 --> 01:14:24,000
behind every flag of the United Nations.

886
01:14:24,000 --> 01:14:29,000
And we were going to go in with the delegation of James Foreman, Stokeley Carmichael myself and so on.

887
01:14:29,000 --> 01:14:37,000
But when we got to the SNCC office and had the meeting with James Foreman and Stokeley Carmichael, it ended up into a big argument.

888
01:14:37,000 --> 01:14:47,000
And almost a fist fight. And we stormed out of the office and the coalition between SNCC and the Black Panther Party was dead at that point.

889
01:14:47,000 --> 01:14:52,000
That was it. And James Foreman was the one that was supposed to get us into the UN.

890
01:14:52,000 --> 01:15:01,000
So we had to find somebody else. We found this from a main Mallory who was one of the leaders, founders of the Black Power Movement.

891
01:15:01,000 --> 01:15:07,000
And so we got a small audience with a 10th and near delegation.

892
01:15:07,000 --> 01:15:14,000
This was June of 68.

893
01:15:14,000 --> 01:15:20,000
Let's try to think in terms of when the former gets the Black manifesto.

894
01:15:20,000 --> 01:15:22,000
Twitter met right around that same time.

895
01:15:22,000 --> 01:15:27,000
Yeah, it probably was.

896
01:15:27,000 --> 01:15:38,000
So you know, it was a power struggle because James Foreman, he had been around longer and he felt that because he had bought some of his field marshals up there to the meeting.

897
01:15:38,000 --> 01:15:43,000
I mean, not to the meeting, but to be in the SNCC office while we were there.

898
01:15:43,000 --> 01:15:49,000
And I just remember them not being very friendly and some tension going on there.

899
01:15:49,000 --> 01:16:01,000
So, you know, I come back to Seattle and only a week after I've been in Seattle, the I'm on my way to the office.

900
01:16:01,000 --> 01:16:06,000
And I see police cars in front of the office and I started to turn around.

901
01:16:06,000 --> 01:16:13,000
I said, let me go find out what's going on. I go down there and ask me, are you here in Dixon? I said, yeah, there's your under arrest.

902
01:16:14,000 --> 01:16:25,000
So I was arrested along with Curtis Harris and charged with stealing a typewriter.

903
01:16:25,000 --> 01:16:34,000
Curtis Harris was the one that had been organizing these illegal activities and we didn't know what was going on at the time.

904
01:16:34,000 --> 01:16:38,000
And then he later on would become suspected of being a police informer.

905
01:16:38,000 --> 01:16:42,000
Because I was arrested, we were both arrested and he was released.

906
01:16:42,000 --> 01:16:51,000
And they had a rally down at Garfield because the community heard about what happened until the party organized a big rally at Garfield High School.

907
01:16:51,000 --> 01:16:57,000
And they marched down to the jail and you know demanded my freedom.

908
01:16:57,000 --> 01:17:07,000
They marched back to Garfield and he ruptured into a riot, a major riot of Seattle's first major riot in the last three days.

909
01:17:08,000 --> 01:17:13,000
And so there was a lot of fire bombing and turning over police cars.

910
01:17:13,000 --> 01:17:16,000
At midnight they decided to let me go.

911
01:17:16,000 --> 01:17:21,000
So they let me go at midnight and I picked up by some panthers.

912
01:17:21,000 --> 01:17:23,000
Do they think of that, man?

913
01:17:23,000 --> 01:17:27,000
Yeah, I thought they thought it would calm things down.

914
01:17:27,000 --> 01:17:36,000
But I get out of midnight, there's still a rioting down at Garfield and they got the streets all blocked off and helicopter flying.

915
01:17:36,000 --> 01:17:40,000
So I get to my mother's house and there's some panthers there.

916
01:17:40,000 --> 01:17:42,000
It's about 8, 10, 12 panthers.

917
01:17:42,000 --> 01:17:48,000
Everybody's got their rifles and guns and they want to go down to Garfield and you know engage the enemy.

918
01:17:48,000 --> 01:17:56,000
And so you know they're trying to convince me and so you know I give in and say okay yeah let's go in and go down there.

919
01:17:56,000 --> 01:17:59,000
So we try to make it down the foot.

920
01:17:59,000 --> 01:18:03,000
Helicopter spots us and signs a light on us.

921
01:18:03,000 --> 01:18:10,000
One of the panthers shoots the light out and pretty soon we know that the area is going to be surrounded by police.

922
01:18:10,000 --> 01:18:17,000
It's somebody out there who we know he calls us into his house.

923
01:18:17,000 --> 01:18:22,000
And just as we get into his house, the area is surrounded by police.

924
01:18:22,000 --> 01:18:29,000
This kind of really kicks off kicks off a war between the Black Panther Party and the Seattle Police Department.

925
01:18:29,000 --> 01:18:34,000
And so we go on a campaign of sniping and fire bombing.

926
01:18:34,000 --> 01:18:42,000
And you know we're sniping at the police and pretty soon the Majority Hill we call it Portia.

927
01:18:42,000 --> 01:18:47,000
It gets the name of Portchop Hill which is a Korean battle in Korea.

928
01:18:47,000 --> 01:18:58,000
And police at night they don't come up there unless the three cars deep and with the four men in a car and the right shotguns hang out the window.

929
01:18:58,000 --> 01:19:01,000
This is how tense it's gotten.

930
01:19:01,000 --> 01:19:05,000
And so this goes on all through that whole summer of 68.

931
01:19:05,000 --> 01:19:13,000
And all across the country you know you got people shooting at police you got riots you got people attacking police stations.

932
01:19:13,000 --> 01:19:19,000
You know it's almost like the revolution had come that summer.

933
01:19:19,000 --> 01:19:28,000
Did we ever reach out and try and negotiate with you or you know in a more peaceful way or was it just a situation?

934
01:19:28,000 --> 01:19:33,000
No that wasn't going to happen because we weren't going to sit down and negotiate with them.

935
01:19:33,000 --> 01:19:47,000
But the Seattle Metro did send a delegation up to meet with us because where our office was that's where the bus parked right in front of it.

936
01:19:47,000 --> 01:19:54,000
And so when we open up our office we told the bus to out you can't park there you got to park back there.

937
01:19:54,000 --> 01:20:01,000
And one day we were having a meeting and bus driver decided to test us.

938
01:20:01,000 --> 01:20:05,000
He parked in front of us while we were having a political education meeting.

939
01:20:05,000 --> 01:20:15,000
And Elmer and another Panther went on the bus and you know jumped on the bus driver took his phone out and threw it on top of the roof.

940
01:20:15,000 --> 01:20:23,000
And I got charged with the potential charge so they had a war not for me.

941
01:20:23,000 --> 01:20:30,000
And so I had to go down and turn myself in but the black judge had a black judge and he let me off.

942
01:20:30,000 --> 01:20:38,000
But they did send a delegation down to meet with us to try and negotiate about letting them park their bus there.

943
01:20:38,000 --> 01:20:41,000
And we told them no not while we were here.

944
01:20:41,000 --> 01:20:44,000
And we needed to light lines out.

945
01:20:44,000 --> 01:20:52,000
Yeah we needed to we didn't want our office blocked out because we had painted black Panther Party on there and Panthers on there.

946
01:20:52,000 --> 01:20:57,000
And all the posters on our windows and everything.

947
01:20:57,000 --> 01:21:05,000
So you know we survived that summer of 68 and then the fall you know first Panther is killed by the Seattle Police Department.

948
01:21:05,000 --> 01:21:09,000
Well the Narpsets 17 years old.

949
01:21:09,000 --> 01:21:12,000
What was the circumstances?

950
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:25,000
He was at home you know he was sort of like an underground and that he wasn't a full-time Panther but he bought money by and he bought guns.

951
01:21:25,000 --> 01:21:28,000
He was still guns you know getting money.

952
01:21:28,000 --> 01:21:32,000
He was a hustler but he was still a Panther.

953
01:21:32,000 --> 01:21:35,000
He was a lump in proletariat you know.

954
01:21:35,000 --> 01:21:38,000
So anyway he I guess the police were out looking for him.

955
01:21:38,000 --> 01:21:45,000
He's at home at his mother's apartment and his him and his mother's apartment and up on the third floor.

956
01:21:45,000 --> 01:21:50,000
He looks out the window he sees the police there confronting his mother and bothering his mother.

957
01:21:50,000 --> 01:22:00,000
He grabs his rifle. He runs downstairs and he gets involved and they shoot him but they shoot him in the back.

958
01:22:00,000 --> 01:22:06,000
And that was our first casualty.

959
01:22:06,000 --> 01:22:20,000
And there was another casualty in December which came about because he was given an order by somebody to go rob a grocery store and the grocery store owned and killed him.

960
01:22:20,000 --> 01:22:29,000
So that's when we started getting hit to you know something else is going on that we don't know about.

961
01:22:29,000 --> 01:22:34,000
And so then my trial starts in December.

962
01:22:34,000 --> 01:22:44,000
I have really a good lawyer this lawyer who eventually became a federal Supreme Court judge here in the state of Washington.

963
01:22:44,000 --> 01:22:50,000
He was considered at the time to be one of the finest lawyers in the state of Washington.

964
01:22:50,000 --> 01:23:00,000
He comes and volunteers take my case because what had happened was when we were trying to get all our things that we needed for our office typewriter,

965
01:23:00,000 --> 01:23:02,000
desking all those things.

966
01:23:02,000 --> 01:23:05,000
There was an informer that came into the party.

967
01:23:05,000 --> 01:23:10,000
So this guy says hey man so and so is going to give us a typewriter down at the model city.

968
01:23:10,000 --> 01:23:14,000
He said we can come down there after five while we got to do is going there and get it.

969
01:23:14,000 --> 01:23:16,000
He'll leave the door open for us.

970
01:23:16,000 --> 01:23:19,000
So I said okay let's go down there.

971
01:23:19,000 --> 01:23:22,000
I was excited yeah we're going to get a brand new typewriter.

972
01:23:22,000 --> 01:23:26,000
Excuse me so I carried it out.

973
01:23:26,000 --> 01:23:30,000
I carried it out of there and I carried it into the office.

974
01:23:30,000 --> 01:23:37,000
And a block away with the plane closed the tectas watching me carry it into the office.

975
01:23:37,000 --> 01:23:40,000
The whole thing was a setup.

976
01:23:40,000 --> 01:23:51,000
So when the trial comes there's a secret witness that they adjourn the hearing to wait for the secret witness.

977
01:23:51,000 --> 01:23:53,000
So everybody's waiting for the secret witness.

978
01:23:53,000 --> 01:23:58,000
Who is going to be the secret witness and he never shows up.

979
01:23:58,000 --> 01:24:02,000
So I'm found not guilty.

980
01:24:02,000 --> 01:24:06,000
I'm found not guilty so.

981
01:24:06,000 --> 01:24:10,000
So anyway I end up going we end up having a purge.

982
01:24:10,000 --> 01:24:15,000
We get rid of a lot of people and then we start the breakfast for school children program.

983
01:24:15,000 --> 01:24:20,000
And there were people who didn't think that was revolutionary serving breakfast for school children.

984
01:24:20,000 --> 01:24:27,000
We opened up our first breakfast program at Majorna Presbyterian Church.

985
01:24:27,000 --> 01:24:32,000
That was in that was in the winter of 69.

986
01:24:32,000 --> 01:24:36,000
Can I ask about the philosophy there?

987
01:24:36,000 --> 01:24:46,000
So yeah this sort of maybe too competing camps is continuing our revolution or meeting basic needs in the community.

988
01:24:46,000 --> 01:24:51,000
Talk a little bit about how that conversation was happening in the party.

989
01:24:51,000 --> 01:24:53,000
Yeah are we ready?

990
01:24:53,000 --> 01:24:54,000
Yeah we're ready.

991
01:24:54,000 --> 01:25:05,000
And this was always this you know this was the the dual nature of the black Panther Party is that there were elements in the party that believed in arm guerrilla warfare.

992
01:25:05,000 --> 01:25:07,000
And they wanted to go do that.

993
01:25:07,000 --> 01:25:10,000
And Elders Cleaver was a chief proponent of that.

994
01:25:10,000 --> 01:25:15,000
He is the one that caused that incident where little Bobby Hutton was killed.

995
01:25:15,000 --> 01:25:20,000
And so there were you know people in the party who related to personalities.

996
01:25:20,000 --> 01:25:23,000
There were people who loved the personality of you.

997
01:25:23,000 --> 01:25:27,000
There are people who loved the personality of Bobby Sia.

998
01:25:27,000 --> 01:25:30,000
And there are people who loved the personality of Elders.

999
01:25:30,000 --> 01:25:37,000
And so they were willing to they thought that this was the way that we should be going.

1000
01:25:37,000 --> 01:25:43,000
So but anyway Elders has to go in exile you know and I think by 1970 he goes in exile.

1001
01:25:43,000 --> 01:25:50,000
And he goes from Cuba and then eventually is living in Algeria where we're the black Panther Party is given diplomatic status.

1002
01:25:50,000 --> 01:25:54,000
And as well as a diplomatic compound.

1003
01:25:54,000 --> 01:26:10,000
So you know and but this is still even though he's not in the country that still is still a continuing struggle in the party of you know community program.

1004
01:26:10,000 --> 01:26:16,000
So we go on and start many more community programs than the weatherman underground takes off.

1005
01:26:16,000 --> 01:26:20,000
And the East Coast Panthers.

1006
01:26:20,000 --> 01:26:25,000
And Bobby Seal is one of those who is a real proponent of a community program.

1007
01:26:25,000 --> 01:26:28,000
Yeah definitely.

1008
01:26:28,000 --> 01:26:29,000
Yeah.

1009
01:26:29,000 --> 01:26:33,000
And then so I go down to Oakland in 1969.

1010
01:26:33,000 --> 01:26:36,000
Bobby said I go down there and things aren't going well and Seattle.

1011
01:26:36,000 --> 01:26:39,000
Bobby Seal tells me to stay down there.

1012
01:26:39,000 --> 01:26:51,000
And so I stay down there and you know I go back down with my family and I'm you know getting training because this is what they instituted after I had become captain was a new chapters in branches.

1013
01:26:51,000 --> 01:26:57,000
They people had to come to Oakland and stay there for a while but they didn't happen with me because we were a new chapter.

1014
01:26:57,000 --> 01:27:02,000
So now I'm going to my kind of Panther training.

1015
01:27:02,000 --> 01:27:05,000
And I'm going to leave you in Oakland.

1016
01:27:05,000 --> 01:27:16,000
Elmer is running things and we had already started to purge before I went down there we had already purged Curtis Harris and a whole bunch of other people.

1017
01:27:16,000 --> 01:27:21,000
And so I told Elmer to just get rid of the rest.

1018
01:27:21,000 --> 01:27:29,000
Did that ever come back on you any of the purges of those people I imagine people weren't happy?

1019
01:27:29,000 --> 01:27:34,000
No, no, no, no, it didn't even come back and not necessarily.

1020
01:27:34,000 --> 01:27:39,000
I mean, yeah, I mean they were, my brother got threatened in Garfield high school.

1021
01:27:39,000 --> 01:27:42,000
Some of them came up there with guns and threatened him.

1022
01:27:42,000 --> 01:27:50,000
So, but you know they knew not to not to really mess with us.

1023
01:27:50,000 --> 01:28:01,000
So, when I'm down in Oakland, Bobby Seale gets kidnapped by the FBI and he's taken driven to Chicago by car.

1024
01:28:01,000 --> 01:28:03,000
Nobody knows where he's at.

1025
01:28:03,000 --> 01:28:05,000
And he goes through the whole Chicago trial.

1026
01:28:05,000 --> 01:28:10,000
They gag him, they chain him down to the chair.

1027
01:28:10,000 --> 01:28:14,000
And so David, here you take over the leadership of the party.

1028
01:28:14,000 --> 01:28:17,000
So, Eldritch is the next ex-Hewis in prison.

1029
01:28:17,000 --> 01:28:20,000
Bobby is now in jail.

1030
01:28:20,000 --> 01:28:23,000
And so the party is under attack.

1031
01:28:23,000 --> 01:28:32,000
FBI, a J.Kuhuver, they said that amongst themselves they were going to have us eliminated by 1969.

1032
01:28:32,000 --> 01:28:40,000
So, in January of 1969, Bunchy Carter and Eldritch John Huggins,

1033
01:28:40,000 --> 01:28:46,000
the two leaders of the Southern California chapter are assassinated.

1034
01:28:46,000 --> 01:28:53,000
Eleven months later, Fred Hampton, and his Chicago chapter is assassinated.

1035
01:28:53,000 --> 01:29:00,000
J.Kuhuver had sent out a memo that he wanted to check, three chapters destroyed,

1036
01:29:00,000 --> 01:29:03,000
Chicago, LA, and Seattle.

1037
01:29:03,000 --> 01:29:09,000
So, when Bobby is kidnapped and gone to jail, I'm sent back to Seattle.

1038
01:29:09,000 --> 01:29:12,000
We've got to start this campaign to try to free Seattle.

1039
01:29:12,000 --> 01:29:17,000
So, me and my brother, we start organizing the Seattle chapter.

1040
01:29:17,000 --> 01:29:25,000
We get orders to close down the storefronts and move into a community, move into a house in the communities that we find a duplex.

1041
01:29:25,000 --> 01:29:29,000
And we open up a community center in the duplex.

1042
01:29:29,000 --> 01:29:32,000
We start fortifying our office with sandbags.

1043
01:29:32,000 --> 01:29:38,000
Because we meet with this guy from the Justice Department of Black man, says he wants to meet with us.

1044
01:29:38,000 --> 01:29:41,000
We don't want to meet with him. We put it off. We put it off.

1045
01:29:41,000 --> 01:29:45,000
Finally, he says it's a matter of life and death. So, we meet with him.

1046
01:29:45,000 --> 01:29:48,000
He tells us that they're going to come in and kill us.

1047
01:29:48,000 --> 01:29:50,000
That they're going to raid us and kill us.

1048
01:29:50,000 --> 01:29:58,000
So, we start fortifying our office with sandbags and double sandbags and steal fortifications on the doors and on the windows.

1049
01:29:58,000 --> 01:30:00,000
Is he threatening you or is he threatening you?

1050
01:30:00,000 --> 01:30:02,000
No, he's not threatening me. He's tipping us off.

1051
01:30:02,000 --> 01:30:05,000
And what was motivated him, do you think?

1052
01:30:05,000 --> 01:30:08,000
He's black. And he's from Seattle.

1053
01:30:08,000 --> 01:30:13,000
And he tells us they're coming to kill you guys.

1054
01:30:13,000 --> 01:30:16,000
He really did tip us off.

1055
01:30:16,000 --> 01:30:19,000
So, we start preparing.

1056
01:30:19,000 --> 01:30:23,000
And we had already gotten orders anyway to fortify our offices.

1057
01:30:23,000 --> 01:30:31,000
So, all the Panther chapters all across the country are fortifying their office with sandbags and bunkers and all kinds of things.

1058
01:30:31,000 --> 01:30:40,000
And so, my brother and I, we're still students at the UDUB technically and we get our last financial aid checks, $1,700 each.

1059
01:30:40,000 --> 01:30:42,000
We spend our whole checks.

1060
01:30:42,000 --> 01:30:52,000
That whole all that money went on guns and munitions, gas masks, flat jackets and things that fortify our office, things that protect us.

1061
01:30:52,000 --> 01:30:58,000
That was the most important thing is that we're going to defend ourselves and protect ourselves.

1062
01:30:58,000 --> 01:31:06,000
But we had also started creating the breakfast program, then expanding the breakfast program, the five breakfast program locations in Seattle.

1063
01:31:06,000 --> 01:31:11,000
And Black Panther part of our cross the country is expanding these survival programs.

1064
01:31:11,000 --> 01:31:14,000
You know, we started the first three medical clinic in Seattle.

1065
01:31:14,000 --> 01:31:17,000
The party opens up 11 medical clinics all across the country.

1066
01:31:17,000 --> 01:31:20,000
And in some places they started a free ambulance program.

1067
01:31:20,000 --> 01:31:27,000
We started the first food bank program, you know, which is now a nationwide program and the state of Washington is a statewide program.

1068
01:31:27,000 --> 01:31:36,000
Black Panther Party, as far as the first food bank program, which is a staple now, the way that people survive and our clinics.

1069
01:31:36,000 --> 01:31:40,000
And so, we're a free legal aid program. We start a free legal aid program.

1070
01:31:40,000 --> 01:31:47,000
We start the bushing the prisons program. Somebody gives us a 35 passenger bus to use to go to all the prisons.

1071
01:31:47,000 --> 01:31:50,000
Then we're, you know, we're able to fund these programs.

1072
01:31:50,000 --> 01:31:55,000
We get orders that every Panther has to sell 100 papers a day.

1073
01:31:55,000 --> 01:32:01,000
So we're selling. So we got a lot of, some of the funds came from the newspaper.

1074
01:32:01,000 --> 01:32:09,000
But we had somebody who was a breakfast program coordinator, the medical clinic coordinator, the Liberation School coordinator.

1075
01:32:09,000 --> 01:32:16,000
And they had to go out and hustle. They had to go out and get money for their program to get resources for their programs.

1076
01:32:16,000 --> 01:32:21,000
Then there's wealthy people who, liberal who are donating money.

1077
01:32:21,000 --> 01:32:26,000
And we got a lot of money that was donated from Japanese, older Japanese.

1078
01:32:26,000 --> 01:32:31,000
And I didn't know why at the time, but I learned about the internment program.

1079
01:32:31,000 --> 01:32:36,000
That's why they were contributing to us.

1080
01:32:36,000 --> 01:32:38,000
So...

1081
01:32:38,000 --> 01:32:42,000
What's going on in your personal life right now? Are you still single or...?

1082
01:32:42,000 --> 01:32:49,000
Oh, I'd become married. And if 68 I got married, my son was born in 69.

1083
01:32:49,000 --> 01:32:52,000
So, you know, I got a little family going on.

1084
01:32:52,000 --> 01:32:54,000
So does that change things for you?

1085
01:32:54,000 --> 01:32:56,000
No, because my wife is in the party as well.

1086
01:32:56,000 --> 01:33:01,000
So, you know, it's just, you know, we're all just moving forward.

1087
01:33:01,000 --> 01:33:08,000
And, you know, like you said early on that, you know, you're going from these highs and lows.

1088
01:33:08,000 --> 01:33:11,000
We're really going through highs and lows now.

1089
01:33:11,000 --> 01:33:15,000
We're really going. It's just like everything is moving.

1090
01:33:15,000 --> 01:33:18,000
So, you know, we got to sell papers every day.

1091
01:33:18,000 --> 01:33:21,000
Everybody has to go on the field and sell papers every day.

1092
01:33:21,000 --> 01:33:25,000
Then we have, you know, the breakfast program.

1093
01:33:25,000 --> 01:33:28,000
We got to get up early in the morning, go to the breakfast program.

1094
01:33:28,000 --> 01:33:30,000
You know, we're running all these programs.

1095
01:33:30,000 --> 01:33:33,000
And no government funding is coming in.

1096
01:33:33,000 --> 01:33:37,000
But it's really a great time, you know, because, you know, we're so energized.

1097
01:33:37,000 --> 01:33:39,000
We're young. We got a lot of energy.

1098
01:33:39,000 --> 01:33:42,000
And we're able to do all these things.

1099
01:33:42,000 --> 01:33:47,000
And we're fairly. We're not afraid of anything, you know.

1100
01:33:47,000 --> 01:33:52,000
And so, it's just like 20 of us, 25 of us compared to 200 of us.

1101
01:33:52,000 --> 01:33:55,000
And we're doing so much work.

1102
01:33:55,000 --> 01:34:00,000
And not only do we have to do all this work, but when we come in from the field,

1103
01:34:00,000 --> 01:34:02,000
we all eat together communally.

1104
01:34:02,000 --> 01:34:04,000
And we have little graduation class.

1105
01:34:04,000 --> 01:34:06,000
We have weapon class.

1106
01:34:06,000 --> 01:34:11,000
And everybody has to pull security two hours a night, ten to twelve, two out of two, two to four, four to six.

1107
01:34:11,000 --> 01:34:16,000
So, you know, it's just constant thing.

1108
01:34:16,000 --> 01:34:19,000
It's very intense lifestyle, you know.

1109
01:34:19,000 --> 01:34:25,000
But, you know, we're, you know, this is what we want to do.

1110
01:34:25,000 --> 01:34:31,000
And so they began, so this attack, you know, this attack this guy is talking about.

1111
01:34:31,000 --> 01:34:33,000
And they start in Chicago.

1112
01:34:33,000 --> 01:34:35,000
They go in there. They kill Fred Hampton.

1113
01:34:35,000 --> 01:34:39,000
They try, they wanted to kill Bobby Rush, but he wasn't there.

1114
01:34:39,000 --> 01:34:44,000
And then four or five days later, they go to LA.

1115
01:34:44,000 --> 01:34:48,000
And they raid the LA office with the LA Panthers, a very military man.

1116
01:34:48,000 --> 01:34:50,000
They got a bunker built inside.

1117
01:34:50,000 --> 01:34:51,000
They never shoot out.

1118
01:34:51,000 --> 01:34:52,000
They're ready.

1119
01:34:52,000 --> 01:34:53,000
It has to six, eight hours, you know.

1120
01:34:53,000 --> 01:34:57,000
And the only thing that stopped them was they run out of ammunition.

1121
01:34:57,000 --> 01:34:59,000
And they surrender.

1122
01:34:59,000 --> 01:35:01,000
Then ATF comes to Seattle.

1123
01:35:01,000 --> 01:35:02,000
They go to Mara West Omen.

1124
01:35:02,000 --> 01:35:05,000
The Mara West Omen says, I'm not going to let you do that.

1125
01:35:05,000 --> 01:35:07,000
Because he saw what happened in Chicago.

1126
01:35:07,000 --> 01:35:08,000
He saw what happened in LA.

1127
01:35:08,000 --> 01:35:10,000
He said, it was a much smaller place.

1128
01:35:10,000 --> 01:35:11,000
Everybody knows us.

1129
01:35:11,000 --> 01:35:12,000
Everybody knows us.

1130
01:35:12,000 --> 01:35:17,000
We are, we got, probably, as these programs, we got all these programs we're doing.

1131
01:35:17,000 --> 01:35:21,000
We're testing for sickle cell anemia.

1132
01:35:21,000 --> 01:35:26,000
We did the first mass testing of sickle cell anemia in Walla Walla, Peter Prison.

1133
01:35:26,000 --> 01:35:28,000
So, and me and people are depending upon us.

1134
01:35:28,000 --> 01:35:32,000
So how is he going to let the ATF come in there and try to kill us?

1135
01:35:32,000 --> 01:35:34,000
So he says no.

1136
01:35:34,000 --> 01:35:35,000
And so...

1137
01:35:35,000 --> 01:35:39,000
And you had any dealings with someone before this?

1138
01:35:39,000 --> 01:35:40,000
No, not really.

1139
01:35:40,000 --> 01:35:41,000
Not really.

1140
01:35:41,000 --> 01:35:47,000
But we had continuous attempts to raid our office by the Seattle Police Department.

1141
01:35:47,000 --> 01:35:52,000
And there were two policemen that they assigned just to harass us, arrest us.

1142
01:35:52,000 --> 01:35:59,000
And so, you know, it's been a constant battle just with the Seattle Police Department fighting them, you know.

1143
01:35:59,000 --> 01:36:05,000
And dealing with them and dealing with the issues that they're causing in the community as well.

1144
01:36:05,000 --> 01:36:08,000
Other black officers in the police are the...

1145
01:36:08,000 --> 01:36:09,000
There's only one.

1146
01:36:09,000 --> 01:36:11,000
Only one, yeah.

1147
01:36:11,000 --> 01:36:12,000
Yeah.

1148
01:36:12,000 --> 01:36:18,000
And he does intervene in the behalf of a panther Leon Valentine Hobbes.

1149
01:36:18,000 --> 01:36:21,000
So...

1150
01:36:21,000 --> 01:36:25,000
And so when Mara West all mistakes up,

1151
01:36:26,000 --> 01:36:35,000
then other municipalities start sticking up too and not allowing these raids to take place.

1152
01:36:35,000 --> 01:36:38,000
And when Mara...

1153
01:36:38,000 --> 01:36:42,000
West all men goes back to DC for the Mara's Convention.

1154
01:36:42,000 --> 01:36:44,000
These told he's not welcome.

1155
01:36:44,000 --> 01:36:45,000
And they don't let him in.

1156
01:36:45,000 --> 01:36:46,000
Oh, really?

1157
01:36:46,000 --> 01:36:47,000
Yeah.

1158
01:36:47,000 --> 01:36:49,000
Because Nixon, you know, this is part of Nixon's plan.

1159
01:36:49,000 --> 01:36:50,000
He wanted...

1160
01:36:50,000 --> 01:36:51,000
This is what he wanted.

1161
01:36:51,000 --> 01:36:53,000
You know, I was on Nixon's enemy list.

1162
01:36:53,000 --> 01:36:55,000
He had an enemy list of 100.

1163
01:36:55,000 --> 01:36:59,000
I'm sure most of those people were panthers that were on that enemy list.

1164
01:36:59,000 --> 01:37:04,000
Seattle Police Department also put out a contract on my head at $25,000.

1165
01:37:04,000 --> 01:37:09,000
This was during the summer of 1968 to stop the fire bombing.

1166
01:37:09,000 --> 01:37:14,000
Because time magazine had a chart of cities during the summer of 1968.

1167
01:37:14,000 --> 01:37:16,000
They had two charts.

1168
01:37:16,000 --> 01:37:19,000
The chart of fire bombings and the chart of sniping.

1169
01:37:19,000 --> 01:37:24,000
And Seattle was number one on fire bombing compared to Chicago, Detroit,

1170
01:37:24,000 --> 01:37:26,000
and all the other places were number one.

1171
01:37:26,000 --> 01:37:29,000
And then we were number two in sniping.

1172
01:37:29,000 --> 01:37:36,000
So they felt that if they got rid of me, that they could in the fire bombing campaign.

1173
01:37:36,000 --> 01:37:42,000
And the fire bombing campaign was really directed at racist establishments, you know,

1174
01:37:42,000 --> 01:37:45,000
and outside of the community.

1175
01:37:45,000 --> 01:37:50,000
And you know, it got out of hand because there were some people who weren't

1176
01:37:50,000 --> 01:37:54,000
necessarily racist establishments that they did get fire bomb.

1177
01:37:54,000 --> 01:37:58,000
And that was casualties of war, you know.

1178
01:37:58,000 --> 01:38:03,000
But the targets chosen collectively.

1179
01:38:03,000 --> 01:38:10,000
Yeah, we chose targets collectively, but there were people who went off and did their own thing.

1180
01:38:10,000 --> 01:38:13,000
That was unfortunate.

1181
01:38:13,000 --> 01:38:18,000
So this guy Curtis Harris, this is during the summer of 1968.

1182
01:38:18,000 --> 01:38:25,000
I failed to mention this, but we got our hands on some dynamite.

1183
01:38:25,000 --> 01:38:30,000
And we left three, two people to watch the dynamite.

1184
01:38:30,000 --> 01:38:34,000
And we went somewhere and we came back and the dynamite was gone.

1185
01:38:34,000 --> 01:38:35,000
We said, we're going to have to the down.

1186
01:38:35,000 --> 01:38:38,000
All the police came in here and took it.

1187
01:38:38,000 --> 01:38:41,000
So we thought that was strange.

1188
01:38:41,000 --> 01:38:44,000
They were in police informants.

1189
01:38:44,000 --> 01:38:52,000
So about a couple of days later, these two police informants and Curtis Harris,

1190
01:38:52,000 --> 01:38:58,000
I'm closing office up one night and they said, we're going to Aaron, we're going to walk you home this summer.

1191
01:38:58,000 --> 01:39:01,000
68 when things are really hot.

1192
01:39:01,000 --> 01:39:06,000
And I thought that was unusual because they had never volunteered to walk me home before.

1193
01:39:06,000 --> 01:39:09,000
So you usually have security or bodyguards?

1194
01:39:09,000 --> 01:39:10,000
No, I didn't.

1195
01:39:10,000 --> 01:39:11,000
I didn't.

1196
01:39:11,000 --> 01:39:17,000
But there was one brother named Lou Jack, who said he was going to be my bodyguard.

1197
01:39:17,000 --> 01:39:19,000
And so he was with me quite a bit.

1198
01:39:19,000 --> 01:39:25,000
There was a story that he used to sleep in his car in front of my house.

1199
01:39:25,000 --> 01:39:31,000
But Lou Jack had become part of this other thing that was going on.

1200
01:39:31,000 --> 01:39:34,000
So anyway, these guys are going to walk me home.

1201
01:39:34,000 --> 01:39:37,000
They're going to walk me halfway there.

1202
01:39:37,000 --> 01:39:39,000
Police car drives by.

1203
01:39:39,000 --> 01:39:43,000
One of them pulls his gun out and shoots at the fire at the police.

1204
01:39:43,000 --> 01:39:46,000
And then I look around, they're gone.

1205
01:39:46,000 --> 01:39:48,000
They disappear.

1206
01:39:48,000 --> 01:39:51,000
And I knew that I better disappear.

1207
01:39:51,000 --> 01:39:54,000
So I'm trying to find somewhere to hide frantically.

1208
01:39:54,000 --> 01:39:57,000
And I run into the backyard.

1209
01:39:57,000 --> 01:40:03,000
And I said, damn, there's no escape from this backyard because it's got these high-wire bushes and fence are all way around.

1210
01:40:03,000 --> 01:40:05,000
So the police car is driving up.

1211
01:40:05,000 --> 01:40:08,000
I hear the police talking to themselves.

1212
01:40:08,000 --> 01:40:11,000
And then I hear them running up the stairs towards where I'm at.

1213
01:40:11,000 --> 01:40:13,000
And I pulled my gun out.

1214
01:40:13,000 --> 01:40:17,000
And I'm thinking, I'm dead.

1215
01:40:17,000 --> 01:40:19,000
A man comes out on the porch.

1216
01:40:19,000 --> 01:40:20,000
I knew the man.

1217
01:40:20,000 --> 01:40:21,000
I knew his kids.

1218
01:40:21,000 --> 01:40:22,000
I grew up with his kids.

1219
01:40:22,000 --> 01:40:27,000
He told his kids I had to hang around with me and my brother when we joined the party, which I can understand.

1220
01:40:27,000 --> 01:40:30,000
So he calls me and I run into his house.

1221
01:40:30,000 --> 01:40:32,000
And just there's a door close.

1222
01:40:32,000 --> 01:40:34,000
The police come into the yard.

1223
01:40:34,000 --> 01:40:36,000
And we're watching them.

1224
01:40:36,000 --> 01:40:37,000
They're searching.

1225
01:40:37,000 --> 01:40:41,000
And they go back out and they're looking under cars and they're looking under bushes and everything.

1226
01:40:41,000 --> 01:40:43,000
And so we wait and they leave.

1227
01:40:43,000 --> 01:40:47,000
And then after they left, I run home.

1228
01:40:47,000 --> 01:40:56,000
So anyway, getting back to what happened with Mayor West Omen.

1229
01:40:56,000 --> 01:41:08,000
So it also, it starts an investigation into not only the activities of the Black Panther Party, but also the response by the FBI.

1230
01:41:08,000 --> 01:41:21,000
And so because of this investigation, they have to stop those covert raids that they were doing on the Black Panther Party from 68 all the way to 69 where a lot of Panthers were arrested.

1231
01:41:21,000 --> 01:41:28,000
Many charged with long, long, many years in prison.

1232
01:41:28,000 --> 01:41:36,000
And so finally that kind of stops somewhat.

1233
01:41:36,000 --> 01:41:41,000
So then we're moving forward our programs.

1234
01:41:41,000 --> 01:41:48,000
And then in 70, I think it was about 71.

1235
01:41:48,000 --> 01:41:55,000
In the fall of 71, me and another Conrad, we decided to take our weapons out.

1236
01:41:55,000 --> 01:41:59,000
All the weapons, we get them all together and put them in his step van.

1237
01:41:59,000 --> 01:42:01,000
We're going to take them out and test them.

1238
01:42:01,000 --> 01:42:03,000
So we take them all out and we're testing them.

1239
01:42:03,000 --> 01:42:08,000
We test all the weapons itself for the last one, which was a shotgun.

1240
01:42:08,000 --> 01:42:13,000
I had a riot 18 shotgun that I purchased in Oakland and a band that attached me on it.

1241
01:42:13,000 --> 01:42:17,000
And I had my own bandit layer of shells that I used.

1242
01:42:17,000 --> 01:42:23,000
And you know, my bandit layer oftentimes was in the office and everybody knew that was my bandit layer.

1243
01:42:23,000 --> 01:42:28,000
So big Malcolm says, Aaron, this is your weapon. You go in fire.

1244
01:42:28,000 --> 01:42:31,000
And we have been smoking some hash on the way there.

1245
01:42:31,000 --> 01:42:34,000
I put the shutter shotgun up to my shoulder.

1246
01:42:34,000 --> 01:42:36,000
Something tells me don't fire it for my shoulder.

1247
01:42:36,000 --> 01:42:39,000
I bring it down here, fire from here.

1248
01:42:39,000 --> 01:42:44,000
As soon as the firing pin hits the primer, the gun explodes.

1249
01:42:44,000 --> 01:42:47,000
And you know, blows my arm halfway off.

1250
01:42:47,000 --> 01:42:49,000
So I got all this.

1251
01:42:49,000 --> 01:42:53,000
And I got steel rod and two plates on my arm.

1252
01:42:53,000 --> 01:42:58,000
And you know, I go through about four surgeries.

1253
01:42:58,000 --> 01:43:04,000
But we had the bullets tested and found out that the gunpowder had been taken out.

1254
01:43:04,000 --> 01:43:08,000
And high explosives had been put in its place.

1255
01:43:08,000 --> 01:43:12,000
So it was definitely another assassination attempt.

1256
01:43:12,000 --> 01:43:18,000
So when I was back in the office within three days, you know, with my arm cast.

1257
01:43:18,000 --> 01:43:21,000
Because we just had too much work to do here.

1258
01:43:21,000 --> 01:43:24,000
If that guy had been up out of her height.

1259
01:43:24,000 --> 01:43:26,000
Yeah, I'm going to blew my head.

1260
01:43:26,000 --> 01:43:30,000
I wouldn't be here.

1261
01:43:30,000 --> 01:43:37,000
So and shortly after that, there's a split between the black panther part.

1262
01:43:37,000 --> 01:43:39,000
That's when the split happens.

1263
01:43:39,000 --> 01:43:42,000
Because he we get released from prison.

1264
01:43:42,000 --> 01:43:45,000
And there's a lot of high hopes.

1265
01:43:45,000 --> 01:43:49,000
And then him and Eldridge get on a, you know, a talk show.

1266
01:43:49,000 --> 01:43:53,000
Letters have been sent to Eldridge in Algeria.

1267
01:43:53,000 --> 01:43:55,000
They're saying he wants to kill you.

1268
01:43:55,000 --> 01:43:59,000
They've been letters sent to Huey saying, Eldridge wants to kill you.

1269
01:43:59,000 --> 01:44:11,000
So they were FBI was fostering already the strain relationships and the distance that they had between each other.

1270
01:44:11,000 --> 01:44:22,000
And so and the New York panthers decide that they want to take orders from the weather underground.

1271
01:44:22,000 --> 01:44:26,000
And they feel that the underground movement is where it's at.

1272
01:44:26,000 --> 01:44:29,000
Huey exfels them from the black panther party.

1273
01:44:29,000 --> 01:44:33,000
And that leads to the split into the party.

1274
01:44:33,000 --> 01:44:36,000
And so.

1275
01:44:36,000 --> 01:44:39,000
And how are you hearing about these things?

1276
01:44:39,000 --> 01:44:42,000
I'm getting, you know, calls from National Hickory.

1277
01:44:42,000 --> 01:44:43,000
I'm called down there.

1278
01:44:43,000 --> 01:44:45,000
I get called down there.

1279
01:44:45,000 --> 01:44:51,000
We're another panther officials from all across the country are called down the open.

1280
01:44:51,000 --> 01:44:54,000
And we're, you know, we're told about the situation.

1281
01:44:54,000 --> 01:44:58,000
And they want to see who side everybody is on.

1282
01:44:58,000 --> 01:45:03,000
And, you know, most of New Jersey and New York go with Eldridge.

1283
01:45:03,000 --> 01:45:05,000
And just about everybody else.

1284
01:45:05,000 --> 01:45:07,000
Except for the Samson system.

1285
01:45:07,000 --> 01:45:10,000
Not some of the Samson system panthers who are real close to Eldridge.

1286
01:45:10,000 --> 01:45:12,000
They go with Eldridge.

1287
01:45:12,000 --> 01:45:16,000
And the Berkeley panthers, they go with Eldridge as well.

1288
01:45:16,000 --> 01:45:22,000
And so now, you know, we're, you know, we're fighting each other, you know, on the streets.

1289
01:45:22,000 --> 01:45:24,000
And people get killed.

1290
01:45:24,000 --> 01:45:30,000
And Huey decides not to have this thing get escalated anymore.

1291
01:45:30,000 --> 01:45:33,000
You know, he could have sent, he could have given the order.

1292
01:45:33,000 --> 01:45:35,000
And we could have had a all out war.

1293
01:45:35,000 --> 01:45:41,000
But Huey says, no, you know, we're not going to go that way.

1294
01:45:42,000 --> 01:45:51,000
So, you decide to, you know, Oakland is going to be a base of operations that we need to have a base.

1295
01:45:51,000 --> 01:45:54,000
And we need to strengthen that base.

1296
01:45:54,000 --> 01:46:03,000
And so, as a centralization campaign, it started panthers of all from all over the country to Oakland, to be stationed in Oakland.

1297
01:46:03,000 --> 01:46:11,000
Elmer had gone to jail, to prison in Oregon for our robbery of a leather coat.

1298
01:46:11,000 --> 01:46:16,000
So when the centralization takes place, you know, he's locked up.

1299
01:46:16,000 --> 01:46:19,000
So we leave a skeleton crew of people in Seattle.

1300
01:46:19,000 --> 01:46:25,000
And before that, before we went down to Oakland, we had let a campaign to get Elmer free.

1301
01:46:25,000 --> 01:46:29,000
We actually got the governor to pardon him.

1302
01:46:29,000 --> 01:46:37,000
Because that's the first time and only time that happened that a governor was going to pardon the black man as a party member.

1303
01:46:37,000 --> 01:46:41,000
But myself and my father and my attorney, we met with the governor.

1304
01:46:41,000 --> 01:46:43,000
And we got him to do this.

1305
01:46:43,000 --> 01:46:48,000
And we had a petition drive as well.

1306
01:46:48,000 --> 01:46:54,000
So we all come down to Oakland as people there from all over the country.

1307
01:46:54,000 --> 01:46:59,000
I come down with my wife and my son.

1308
01:46:59,000 --> 01:47:04,000
I must have been about 10 to 15 of us.

1309
01:47:04,000 --> 01:47:12,000
And we had so well established in Seattle.

1310
01:47:12,000 --> 01:47:16,000
But Elmer was able to come out and recruit new people.

1311
01:47:16,000 --> 01:47:23,000
And they were able to keep the clinic going and expand the clinic and expand the programs and really keep things going.

1312
01:47:23,000 --> 01:47:28,000
And then Oakland, we decided we were going to enter the electoral process.

1313
01:47:28,000 --> 01:47:34,000
You know, the first thing we did is support Shirley Chisholm's campaign for president.

1314
01:47:34,000 --> 01:47:41,000
And we began our organizing our own campaign, the Rumbabis Silver Mayor of Oakland, Lane Brown, the City Council.

1315
01:47:41,000 --> 01:47:44,000
Open up five campaign offices.

1316
01:47:44,000 --> 01:47:47,000
It's a massive four campaign.

1317
01:47:47,000 --> 01:47:56,000
We give away 10,000 bags of groceries with the chicken in every bag as to kick off the campaign at the Oakland Auditorium.

1318
01:47:56,000 --> 01:48:06,000
And I just remember seeing the bags 10,000 empty bags on the floor of the Oakland Auditorium.

1319
01:48:06,000 --> 01:48:11,000
And how we were able to make this thing happen.

1320
01:48:11,000 --> 01:48:23,000
You know, put the chickens in the eggs and potatoes in the can food, loaf of bread, and give it out so that the chicken is still frozen the very next day.

1321
01:48:23,000 --> 01:48:26,000
And it was just a beautiful campaign.

1322
01:48:26,000 --> 01:48:31,000
I was confined to the office as officer of the day.

1323
01:48:31,000 --> 01:48:37,000
I thought I was going to get a high level position in the campaign, but I didn't.

1324
01:48:37,000 --> 01:48:40,000
He really was trying to get rid of me.

1325
01:48:40,000 --> 01:48:44,000
He had gotten rid of other people, and he was trying to get rid of me.

1326
01:48:44,000 --> 01:48:51,000
People would ask me, asked if I'd be included in the security squad that he had set up.

1327
01:48:51,000 --> 01:48:56,000
He had chosen people from different places to be in this security squad.

1328
01:48:56,000 --> 01:49:02,000
And there were people that felt that I should be in, but he would always say no.

1329
01:49:02,000 --> 01:49:06,000
So what do you think was going on there?

1330
01:49:06,000 --> 01:49:09,000
He thought I had too much power.

1331
01:49:09,000 --> 01:49:23,000
I was a threat to him, because he felt that he told somebody that a lot of people had a lot of respect for me in the party.

1332
01:49:23,000 --> 01:49:27,000
And so he was doing that with some really good people.

1333
01:49:27,000 --> 01:49:31,000
He ran off a lot of really good people.

1334
01:49:31,000 --> 01:49:34,000
Eventually we ran, you know, we ran by this campaign.

1335
01:49:34,000 --> 01:49:36,000
It was a massive campaign.

1336
01:49:36,000 --> 01:49:40,000
We didn't win, but we came really close.

1337
01:49:40,000 --> 01:49:46,000
And so other politicians started coming to us, because they saw we had a political machine.

1338
01:49:46,000 --> 01:49:48,000
We couldn't get out the vote.

1339
01:49:48,000 --> 01:49:56,000
We really did. We put 350 people out on the street every day to get people, to register people to vote.

1340
01:49:56,000 --> 01:50:01,000
And the campaign, we put four or five hundred people out on the street.

1341
01:50:01,000 --> 01:50:04,000
We took people out of the homes to the polling places.

1342
01:50:04,000 --> 01:50:07,000
So we did truly have a political campaign.

1343
01:50:07,000 --> 01:50:10,000
Did there were black folks registered or were voting in these days?

1344
01:50:10,000 --> 01:50:15,000
No, they weren't. We met so many people that never voted before and opened.

1345
01:50:15,000 --> 01:50:20,000
Old people never voted, never even registered the vote.

1346
01:50:20,000 --> 01:50:25,000
So that was a very important piece to get these people registered and get them involved in the campaign.

1347
01:50:25,000 --> 01:50:30,000
And these visitors, things on voting day to make sure that people got there.

1348
01:50:30,000 --> 01:50:37,000
Yeah, we had people standing on corners and freeway overpasses that we had vans going to people's homes,

1349
01:50:37,000 --> 01:50:41,000
taking people from the homes to the polling places.

1350
01:50:41,000 --> 01:50:46,000
So we were very much active that whole day, you know, that whole day.

1351
01:50:46,000 --> 01:50:52,000
So, in terms of, you know, I don't know how much I'm worried.

1352
01:50:52,000 --> 01:50:56,000
I'm just curious about how much, I don't know how much you're thinking these things through,

1353
01:50:56,000 --> 01:51:01,000
but, you know, from armed revolution to actually using, you know, the political system.

1354
01:51:01,000 --> 01:51:04,000
And this is a different kind of tactic.

1355
01:51:04,000 --> 01:51:08,000
Yeah, well see, that was the beauty of about the Black Panther Party,

1356
01:51:08,000 --> 01:51:12,000
is that we were netted, never wedded to one tactic, you know.

1357
01:51:12,000 --> 01:51:16,000
And because we read a lot, we understood that nothing stood outside of change,

1358
01:51:16,000 --> 01:51:19,000
that we always had to be adaptable.

1359
01:51:19,000 --> 01:51:23,000
And we always had to be changing, you know, that's why we went from, you know,

1360
01:51:23,000 --> 01:51:27,000
the armed revolution to the breakfast program, the survival program,

1361
01:51:27,000 --> 01:51:31,000
and doing all these programs, and then to the electoral politics,

1362
01:51:31,000 --> 01:51:38,000
we were constantly evolving and constantly changing our tactics to achieve, you know,

1363
01:51:38,000 --> 01:51:41,000
what we were trying to achieve.

1364
01:51:41,000 --> 01:51:46,000
And so, and you know, there was always people on the left who always criticizes

1365
01:51:46,000 --> 01:51:51,000
for, first of all, having the broad coalitions that we had with all the different people.

1366
01:51:51,000 --> 01:51:56,000
And, you know, with the Brown Berets, the Red Guard, the AIM,

1367
01:51:56,000 --> 01:52:01,000
the white, the young patriots and SDS,

1368
01:52:01,000 --> 01:52:07,000
a piece of freedom party, and then now the survival program, you know,

1369
01:52:07,000 --> 01:52:10,000
most revolutionary organizations at that time,

1370
01:52:10,000 --> 01:52:14,000
they didn't think about doing those survival programs, you know, feeding kids,

1371
01:52:14,000 --> 01:52:18,000
and you know, they didn't think that was revolution, but it was very revolutionary.

1372
01:52:18,000 --> 01:52:22,000
And so, then we went from there, and we went to the electoral politics, you know,

1373
01:52:22,000 --> 01:52:27,000
and it just made perfect sense that, you know, we would try to take over the whole

1374
01:52:27,000 --> 01:52:30,000
electoral piece of Oakland.

1375
01:52:30,000 --> 01:52:37,000
That's what was our goal to make Oakland a base of our operations and expand from there.

1376
01:52:37,000 --> 01:52:40,000
It's about changing the system, so we have valor from what we have to do.

1377
01:52:40,000 --> 01:52:44,000
And we could do it with both. But we still had our underground.

1378
01:52:44,000 --> 01:52:47,000
We still had a...

1379
01:52:47,000 --> 01:52:52,000
This was actually before the split, after the split, the underground cave then,

1380
01:52:52,000 --> 01:52:57,000
because there were people who were in the underground who sided with elders,

1381
01:52:57,000 --> 01:53:00,000
and they no longer had the support from the party.

1382
01:53:00,000 --> 01:53:03,000
One of those people was Geronimo, he was kind of caught in the middle,

1383
01:53:03,000 --> 01:53:08,000
and he had a case, and he and Panthers were allowed to testify in this case,

1384
01:53:08,000 --> 01:53:10,000
so he goes to prison.

1385
01:53:10,000 --> 01:53:20,000
So, anyway, then he will become starting cocaine,

1386
01:53:20,000 --> 01:53:29,000
and his whole piece about what he's supposed to be doing,

1387
01:53:29,000 --> 01:53:32,000
and what the party is supposed to be doing really gets distorted,

1388
01:53:32,000 --> 01:53:42,000
and he really begins to become more of a gangster than a revolutionary.

1389
01:53:42,000 --> 01:53:46,000
So you see his personality really starts to change?

1390
01:53:46,000 --> 01:53:49,000
Yeah, cocaine has really changed.

1391
01:53:49,000 --> 01:53:53,000
Plus, the fact that when he went to prison,

1392
01:53:53,000 --> 01:54:00,000
the Black Panther Party was just a small organization based in Oakland and in LA.

1393
01:54:00,000 --> 01:54:07,000
Now, you know, just friends, people he knew, now he comes out as an international organization.

1394
01:54:07,000 --> 01:54:09,000
He's an international hero.

1395
01:54:09,000 --> 01:54:12,000
He's almost on the level of Chagavera, you know,

1396
01:54:12,000 --> 01:54:16,000
and he's got access to all this power and money,

1397
01:54:16,000 --> 01:54:18,000
but he also...

1398
01:54:18,000 --> 01:54:23,000
There's all these people he doesn't know, and he doesn't trust him, you know.

1399
01:54:23,000 --> 01:54:26,000
And we're paranoid, anyway, we're already paranoid.

1400
01:54:26,000 --> 01:54:29,000
We're paranoid about the phone, we're paranoid about so-and-so,

1401
01:54:29,000 --> 01:54:34,000
we're working next to us, and who's an informant, who's not an informant?

1402
01:54:34,000 --> 01:54:37,000
And so then, you know, he comes out and he's paranoid,

1403
01:54:37,000 --> 01:54:40,000
and then he starts not at cocaine, he becomes even more paranoid.

1404
01:54:40,000 --> 01:54:43,000
And I think at some point he really didn't realize,

1405
01:54:43,000 --> 01:54:44,000
he didn't want to...

1406
01:54:44,000 --> 01:54:47,000
This is not really what he wanted to do.

1407
01:54:47,000 --> 01:54:53,000
You know, this is not what the role that he envisioned himself doing.

1408
01:54:53,000 --> 01:54:57,000
He was thrusted up into this role, you know?

1409
01:54:57,000 --> 01:55:01,000
And so he starts dismantling the party.

1410
01:55:01,000 --> 01:55:06,000
So anyway, our contract is put on on his head.

1411
01:55:06,000 --> 01:55:09,000
A warrant is also put on on his head.

1412
01:55:09,000 --> 01:55:14,000
You know, he runs off Bobby Seal, John Seal, many other people,

1413
01:55:14,000 --> 01:55:19,000
and he has to go and flee and go to Cuba and go into exile.

1414
01:55:19,000 --> 01:55:24,000
And Lane Brown becomes the chairperson of the Black Panther Party.

1415
01:55:24,000 --> 01:55:29,000
And so she starts rebuilding the party, and she chooses me as her bodyguard.

1416
01:55:29,000 --> 01:55:32,000
Can you ask this as a service, I've barred,

1417
01:55:32,000 --> 01:55:36,000
if you could talk about the role of women in the party and how women...

1418
01:55:36,000 --> 01:55:42,000
Well, if that were treated, what the philosophy of the party was in terms of including women?

1419
01:55:42,000 --> 01:55:46,000
Yeah. Well, women were considered to be equal in the party.

1420
01:55:46,000 --> 01:55:51,000
They did everything that the men did, and they weren't confined to doing women's chores.

1421
01:55:51,000 --> 01:55:54,000
And first of all, the type of women that joined the party,

1422
01:55:54,000 --> 01:55:56,000
they weren't going to go for that anyway.

1423
01:55:56,000 --> 01:55:59,000
They were some very tough, very demanding women.

1424
01:55:59,000 --> 01:56:02,000
You know, you couldn't pull no crap off over on them.

1425
01:56:02,000 --> 01:56:06,000
And so they were equal, and they served in leadership.

1426
01:56:06,000 --> 01:56:09,000
The Connecticut chapter was run by a woman.

1427
01:56:09,000 --> 01:56:14,000
Erica, again, the Boston chapter, Captain was a woman, Audrey Jones.

1428
01:56:14,000 --> 01:56:18,000
And so you had Panthers, women who were a Lane Brown,

1429
01:56:18,000 --> 01:56:21,000
Kathleen Cleaver on the Central Committee of the Black Panther Party.

1430
01:56:21,000 --> 01:56:27,000
So women had a very prominent, very strong role in the party.

1431
01:56:27,000 --> 01:56:31,000
Now, that doesn't just say that there weren't problems that existed,

1432
01:56:31,000 --> 01:56:40,000
because trying to overcome the whole issue of male dominance in machoism and stuff,

1433
01:56:41,000 --> 01:56:43,000
was very difficult.

1434
01:56:43,000 --> 01:56:47,000
And there were places, in some places, in the Southern California chapter,

1435
01:56:47,000 --> 01:56:54,000
where women were abused, you know, in many ways.

1436
01:56:54,000 --> 01:56:58,000
And so that's where the Lane Brown had come out of.

1437
01:56:58,000 --> 01:57:02,000
Now, here she was, was ahead of the whole Black Panther Party,

1438
01:57:02,000 --> 01:57:04,000
of what was left of it.

1439
01:57:04,000 --> 01:57:07,000
So she began to rebuild the party.

1440
01:57:08,000 --> 01:57:10,000
I'm on her bodyguard.

1441
01:57:10,000 --> 01:57:19,000
Yeah, and she goes to Cuba, and Huey tells her to visit Huey,

1442
01:57:19,000 --> 01:57:24,000
and Huey tells her to ask Lina Wilson,

1443
01:57:24,000 --> 01:57:27,000
a retired superior court judge, if he wanted to be mayor.

1444
01:57:27,000 --> 01:57:30,000
And so we asked him, and he said, yeah,

1445
01:57:30,000 --> 01:57:34,000
and so we start running a campaign to run him from mayor.

1446
01:57:35,000 --> 01:57:37,000
Namin Wau.

1447
01:57:37,000 --> 01:57:39,000
You asked the question, don't you?

1448
01:57:39,000 --> 01:57:40,000
You know what Alexander?

1449
01:57:40,000 --> 01:57:41,000
Yes.

1450
01:57:41,000 --> 01:57:42,000
Yeah.

1451
01:57:42,000 --> 01:57:44,000
Tell me something about her, she's an old friend.

1452
01:57:44,000 --> 01:57:46,000
Oh, wow, wow.

1453
01:57:46,000 --> 01:57:48,000
Bertha Alexander, man.

1454
01:57:50,000 --> 01:57:52,000
If this tall woman, right?

1455
01:57:52,000 --> 01:57:55,000
Yeah, kind of like conflicted, yeah.

1456
01:57:55,000 --> 01:58:01,000
And she worked a lot with big man,

1457
01:58:01,000 --> 01:58:04,000
and big man was the editor of the newspaper,

1458
01:58:04,000 --> 01:58:08,000
and they traveled, they did a lot of traveling around the world,

1459
01:58:08,000 --> 01:58:12,000
you know, talking about where they went to Japan.

1460
01:58:12,000 --> 01:58:15,000
They spent a lot of time in Japan, in South Korea,

1461
01:58:15,000 --> 01:58:17,000
and many other places.

1462
01:58:17,000 --> 01:58:19,000
And she worked on the newspaper too.

1463
01:58:19,000 --> 01:58:25,000
She was a very, you know, very important person, you know, in the party.

1464
01:58:25,000 --> 01:58:26,000
Yeah.

1465
01:58:26,000 --> 01:58:28,000
She's still alive?

1466
01:58:28,000 --> 01:58:29,000
She's still alive.

1467
01:58:30,000 --> 01:58:31,000
Where she is?

1468
01:58:31,000 --> 01:58:34,000
She's in California, so I'm not sure if you can watch Android.

1469
01:58:34,000 --> 01:58:35,000
I'll be there.

1470
01:58:35,000 --> 01:58:36,000
A little self-aware.

1471
01:58:36,000 --> 01:58:37,000
Okay.

1472
01:58:37,000 --> 01:58:40,000
She isn't, she isn't, um,

1473
01:58:40,000 --> 01:58:43,000
she's in my way with dance classes together.

1474
01:58:43,000 --> 01:58:45,000
There were roommates in the whole of Japan.

1475
01:58:45,000 --> 01:58:46,000
Wow.

1476
01:58:46,000 --> 01:58:48,000
But yeah, you tell me you ran into him again.

1477
01:58:48,000 --> 01:58:49,000
Yeah.

1478
01:58:49,000 --> 01:58:50,000
Yeah.

1479
01:58:50,000 --> 01:58:54,000
So, um, well, I'm glad you did.

1480
01:58:54,000 --> 01:58:57,000
I'm so glad to hear that she's alive and doing well.

1481
01:58:57,000 --> 01:58:58,000
Yeah, damn.

1482
01:58:58,000 --> 01:58:59,000
So anyway, uh...

1483
01:58:59,000 --> 01:59:02,000
Is that sort of given, I guess, to the world?

1484
01:59:02,000 --> 01:59:03,000
No.

1485
01:59:03,000 --> 01:59:04,000
Love people are...

1486
01:59:04,000 --> 01:59:12,000
Actually, no, it's not, it's not a given, especially some women.

1487
01:59:12,000 --> 01:59:17,000
Because they had, they did have a hard time with some things.

1488
01:59:17,000 --> 01:59:24,000
But so did a lot of men, you know, and so it just wasn't easy, you know, after it was all over.

1489
01:59:24,000 --> 01:59:32,000
But getting back to the story, when we, uh, before we ran Lionel Wilson's campaign,

1490
01:59:32,000 --> 01:59:40,000
Jerry Brown came to us and asked us to support his mayor for, uh, his bid for governor at the state of California.

1491
01:59:40,000 --> 01:59:46,000
And he had some, uh, close relationships with party members in LA and Elaine Brown knew him.

1492
01:59:46,000 --> 01:59:49,000
So we said, yeah, yeah, we'll support you.

1493
01:59:49,000 --> 01:59:52,000
We'll work in your campaign.

1494
01:59:52,000 --> 01:59:55,000
So, uh, Lauren, they already become the governor.

1495
01:59:55,000 --> 02:00:01,000
And so Elaine is, is spending a lot of time in the governor's office meeting with him.

1496
02:00:01,000 --> 02:00:07,000
And Tony Klein, who was a head legal person in the state of California,

1497
02:00:07,000 --> 02:00:10,000
and then also worked with the party in Southern California.

1498
02:00:10,000 --> 02:00:16,000
So, um, uh, and Elaine is cultivating this relationship.

1499
02:00:16,000 --> 02:00:24,000
Um, Jerry Brown calls Elaine up and says, I have six judgeships that I want to fill in the, in Oakland.

1500
02:00:24,000 --> 02:00:29,000
Can you help me? She says, yes, I'll give, give, give back with you with the name.

1501
02:00:29,000 --> 02:00:34,000
She gives them the name of six black attorneys, and they all become judges.

1502
02:00:34,000 --> 02:00:41,000
And so you could say that we had some control of the judiciary in Oakland because of this.

1503
02:00:41,000 --> 02:00:45,000
And those lawyers knew why they became, uh, judges.

1504
02:00:45,000 --> 02:00:47,000
It was because of the black Panther Party.

1505
02:00:47,000 --> 02:00:50,000
Elaine made sure they understood that.

1506
02:00:50,000 --> 02:00:54,000
So, you know, damn, you know, we got some, we got some power here, you know.

1507
02:00:54,000 --> 02:00:58,000
So there, then we started running Liner Wilson's campaign.

1508
02:00:58,000 --> 02:01:03,000
And Lauren Behold, we put the first black mayor into office in Oakland.

1509
02:01:03,000 --> 02:01:08,000
And then we turned, he's going to point two Panther women to the port of Oakland.

1510
02:01:08,000 --> 02:01:13,000
And this, the Central Committee has made up of mostly women at this time.

1511
02:01:13,000 --> 02:01:18,000
Uh, because Elaine, you know, bought women up and got them on the Central Committee.

1512
02:01:18,000 --> 02:01:20,000
And so now we're in Liner Wilson's office.

1513
02:01:20,000 --> 02:01:22,000
We're running the city.

1514
02:01:22,000 --> 02:01:24,000
Oh, the black Panther Party is running the city.

1515
02:01:24,000 --> 02:01:29,000
We're meeting with the, uh, the, um, yeah, what is that person's name?

1516
02:01:29,000 --> 02:01:31,000
I can't think it was a name.

1517
02:01:31,000 --> 02:01:35,000
But, uh, man, it was, it was, it was really sent.

1518
02:01:35,000 --> 02:01:39,000
Plus we had a private school in a community center.

1519
02:01:39,000 --> 02:01:43,000
And the private school was one of the best private schools in the country.

1520
02:01:43,000 --> 02:01:48,000
It started off as a private school just for Panther kids, but expanded to the community.

1521
02:01:48,000 --> 02:01:55,000
We had people who were doctors and lawyers that had their kids there, as well as kids who came from the housing projects that were students there.

1522
02:01:55,000 --> 02:01:58,000
We had a Marshaar's program.

1523
02:01:58,000 --> 02:02:02,000
It was, uh, on the cover of Black Belt Magazine, it had over 100 students.

1524
02:02:02,000 --> 02:02:09,000
We had, um, we started the first gang intervention program in the Bay Area.

1525
02:02:09,000 --> 02:02:14,000
And we got a Cedar Grant, you know, Cedar was the comprehensive employment program.

1526
02:02:14,000 --> 02:02:17,000
That was one of the best programs the government ever had.

1527
02:02:17,000 --> 02:02:22,000
Uh, they gave money to nonprofits and businesses to hire people.

1528
02:02:22,000 --> 02:02:30,000
And so we, we were able to put 20 Panthers on, on the payroll with, with the big Cedar Grant that we got.

1529
02:02:30,000 --> 02:02:34,000
And that's how we started our gang intervention program.

1530
02:02:34,000 --> 02:02:40,000
And then we started a, a seniors against a fearful environment program where we got gang members.

1531
02:02:40,000 --> 02:02:53,000
We hired gang involved youth to, uh, work with seniors on the weekends when they got to paycheck and escort them to the bank, escort them to the grocery store and so on.

1532
02:02:53,000 --> 02:03:01,000
So, um, and Elaine was able to clean the image up of the Black Panther Party.

1533
02:03:01,000 --> 02:03:06,000
We also had a restaurant, a bar in Grille in downtown Oakland called the Lamp Post.

1534
02:03:06,000 --> 02:03:10,000
We also had, um, a, you know, some other businesses.

1535
02:03:10,000 --> 02:03:17,000
We had a promotion business where we bought Marvin Gaye and Chakka Khan and Earth Wind and Fire and other people to Oakland.

1536
02:03:17,000 --> 02:03:23,000
And I continued to turn around with didn't turn out to be so good.

1537
02:03:23,000 --> 02:03:30,000
Um, and so, you know, um, and then we had these millionaires who all they did was give money to the party.

1538
02:03:30,000 --> 02:03:33,000
And so we were, have bought a lot of property.

1539
02:03:33,000 --> 02:03:37,000
We owned a lot of property, you know, where we had the school was a huge property.

1540
02:03:37,000 --> 02:03:41,000
What about your lunch? We only have a couple of things of the nation.

1541
02:03:41,000 --> 02:03:46,000
And, you know, the island of President Sinnoh Klan and property have businesses.

1542
02:03:46,000 --> 02:03:48,000
I mean, the nation of Islam.

1543
02:03:48,000 --> 02:04:03,000
We had a contentious relationship with them because Huey was, um, when he, before he went into exile, he was, um, was involved in drug operation, you know.

1544
02:04:03,000 --> 02:04:13,000
And, um, he had actually told Farrakhan, they had a meeting with Farrakhan that, you know, you stay over in San Francisco and we'll deal with Oakland.

1545
02:04:13,000 --> 02:04:16,000
And, uh, Huey didn't like heroin.

1546
02:04:16,000 --> 02:04:21,000
He would not allow heroin. He didn't like heroin to be on the streets.

1547
02:04:21,000 --> 02:04:25,000
